post_caption:
SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Sago Lane / Sago Street, in Chinatown

Sago Lane (and Sago Street) gets its name from the many sago factories in the area in mid-1800s Singapore. However, Sago Lane is more famous (or infamous) for another reason - its death houses.

In the past when most Chinese immigrants lived in Chinatown area, the terminally ill would go to a death house where they literally awaited their fate – death.

Now the street has just been revitalised with new arch Chinatown signs and Chinese orientated shelters. 

Of course the main attraction is still the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple. Even if you are not there to pray, the lanterns or lighting (during some festive periods) are an attraction itself.

Given the most depressing covid period, any nice temple or street lighting certainly cheers us up and gives us hope. 🙏

Pulau Ubin, Singapore 🌿
.
For all the nature lovers, Pulau Ubin is a perfect getaway 🌿💚 It is adorned by mangrove trees and beautiful beaches 😍 Exploring this tropical island on a bicycle while cool sea breeze hits your face is one of the best things 😍 All the sweat is worth it when you make a pit stop for that cold Thai coconut water 🥥🤤🤤 
.
If you ever plan to spend more than 4 days in Singapore, would highly recommend saving half a day for this island 😍
.

When one makes their way to Fort Canning, one can hardly miss this huge lawn in front of the Fort Canning Centre. 

This was the lush lawn I had previously mentioned in my earlier post that used to be a Christian Cemetery. 

Here's a short history of this place:

"Developed in 1822 by George Coleman – Singapore’s first architect and Stamford Raffles’ consultant on the first Town Plan – the Fort Canning Christian cemetery had approximately 600 graves interred. 

The cemetery was eventually closed in 1865, and the state of the burial grounds began to deteriorate. In 1953, the City Council exhumed the cemetery and created a “Garden of Memory”."

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct]  Ancient South Indian Temple architectural with a respect for harmonious coexistence re-discovered

Rediscovery is about relooking and appreciate the coexistence of interesting elements in an environment

I learned about Sri Senpaga only recently and decided to re-discover this amazing temple built with ancient South Indian temple architectural style that flourished in the 7th-century Chola dynasty. This temple was established in the 1850s by Ceylonese Tamils from Sri Lanka which explains the differences  from the usual Hindu temple that I have seen.

 Two things captured my attention. Firstly, it is the  21-metre tall, five-tiered structure at the main entrance that looks amazing with the glow from the morning sun. The intrigued details are very impressive. 
Secondly, it was the signage that says “All are welcome”. You need to read the signage in detail to be impressed by how welcoming they are regardless of different race and religion. That signage as well as the temple represents what is unique about Singapore - Our harmonious  coexistence of different races and religions into what is Singapore.

Hope to visit this temple more

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct] Reflection of Joo Chiat’s best ambassadors 

Rediscovery is about having a good listening ear  and keen observation of the place and people.

Joo Chiat is a place with a rich history. We often see elderly around. Some leisurely walking around while others cycle. What is unique is the friendliness of the people. I was there twice recently. On both occasions, I have had elderly (residents or former residents) who came to chitchat with me about the heritage of the place as well as interesting places to shoot. They seem to be the best ambassadors of the place - For their knowledge and their part in the history of this place- to help us rediscover Singapore.

This is a reflection ( literally) of the elderly from Joo Chiat with the colorful peranakan house

Embracing the good light 🚇

| Into the dark
• Sony a6000 + SEL55210 •

While I love bright bold colours that daytime photography can give me, it's quite tough to catch much sunlight after office hours.  So instead, I'm learning to embrace and enjoy night photography. Thankfully, Singapore has so much to offer at night. Bright LED lights from skyscrapers in the CBD area and bustling roads filled with cars almost 24/7. I'm never disappointed when I head out into the night after work is over.

For this set of photos, I chose 3 iconic brands with logos that stand out in the midst of the darkness.

Since the signage reads “Supreme Pork Chop Rice”, there’s just no way I will order anything else besides their pork chop rice. Situated in the basement of a nondescript building along Beach Road, the stall is housed in an area with other F&B outlets. However, the clear favourite stall and the one with the queue is selling pork chop rice. At a cost of $4.30, it comes with a bowl-sized fried rice, some coleslaw, an egg and a glorious piece of deep fried pork chop. The star of the show shines brightly on the pork chop which is neither greasy nor fatty inside. Throw in some of their chilli for that spicy kick which sorts of alleviated the dish even further.

post_caption:
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

The Sembawang Hot Springs Park is a natural hot spring & a public park in Singapore. It is located beside a military camp about 100 metres (330 ft) off the main road, Gambas Avenue. Like hot springs worldwide, it can have health healing properties with proper use in moderation, & its natural spring water had once been bottled commercially by Fraser & Neave, under the brand name of Seletaris. Since its discovery in 1909, the spring has been through a few changes of ownership & potential redevelopment proposals. The hot spring has a rural rustic feel for visitors to unwind from the hustle & bustle of the modern metropolitan city. The National Parks Board took over the ownership of the park for redevelopment, which officially reopened on 4 January 2020. It's one of the two hot springs in Singapore with the other located on Pulau Tekong.

#SingapoRediscovers journey sans the vouchers checking out the historical constitutional documents and oil paintings of Singapore.

At the Siapa Namu Kamu exhibition, especially love the National Language Class painting and how it defined the sign of the times when nationalism was strong and there was a collective desire among our parents and grandparents to forge a national identity. #nationalgallery #singapoliday #art #culture #museum #singaporediscovers #singapoliday

<353> “Probably one of the liveliest places in the heartland of Singapore”

This is a high-ceiling sheltered alley that is lined with a large diversity of small shops that provide every daily need and service you can imagine at the most affordable prices. 

Its most unique feature is the temporary stalls that are set up outside the shops where the sellers promote all sorts of interesting things of the season. 

The place is always bursting at seams in the weekends from morning to the evening. Lured by its local vibes, even on a weekday, there is no short of human traffic.

I would confidently say that it is probably one of the liveliest shopping arcades in the heartland of Singapore. If you drop by, let me show you around.

William

There’s a new way to get to the airport, and it’s also a new recreational option for Singaporeans!
The path connects Changi Airport and East Coast Park, and along this 3.5km route is a permanent outdoor display of more than 20 dinosaur models, from a towering Tyrannosaurus rex to a trio of velociraptors named the Changi Jurassic Mile. 
At the pit stops, there are services such as bicycle rental, pay-per-use showers, a washing bay and a new cafe.

Let me tell you a #dirtylittlesecret. After nine years (and still going damn strong), the #bestshitresturant in town is #stillnotdead. Yes, you heard me right, the least authentic Middle Eastern restaurant, Artichoke, led by the creative genius Chef Bjorn Shen, is still constantly revolutionizing the food and beverage scene based on strong beliefs and faith, without caring less of the norm.
•
The definite and right way of a proper dining experience at Artichoke is to start off with a bag of Turkish bread and a spread of mezzes. Mezzes are essentially a collection of small plates of food served as sharing appetizers to whet your appetite for the mains. What we have on the table are some of the mezzes that are new on the menu such as the Turkish Eggplant ($12), Sea Asparagus ($12) and Crab Toast ($16) while the Hummus with Iraqi Spiced Mushrooms ($14) is an improved version of the previous. The newly band of brothers are perfect to go alongside the Turkish bread, especially the hummus which is creamy, rich and just pure decadent; when paired with the abalone mushrooms that has been seasoned in Baharat, a thyme spice mixed of 7 spices, sautéed with olive oil and garlic. The more interesting dish is the Crab Toast whereby instead of a usual one-biter food, this is Artichoke’s version of a two-biter open-faced “sandwich”, made with blue swimmer crab that’s mixed with Greek yogurt and other ingredients before topped on housebaked brioche. The finishing touches of adding deep-fried chicken skin and ikura creates the differing texture and flavour.
_________________
Artichoke Singapore
Address: 161, Middle Road, Singapore 188978

For generations, Singaporeans affectionately called it "NTUC" despite its official name is "NTUC FairPrice" or "FairPrice" in (@fairpricesg) in short, mainly because this supermarket chain is a co-operative of the National Trades Union Congress (NTUC), the main trade union body in #Singapore.

The first outlet of this chain was first opened in #ToaPayoh (as shown) in 1973 as #NTUC Welcome Supermarket and it is still in operation.

The setting of this supermarket in that era was to allow Singaporeans to buy groceries and other daily necessities at affordable prices because of the high inflation rate back then.

These flats along #Bishan Road, which I snapped from where Bishan Circle Line station is, set themselves apart from those in neighbouring #ToaPayoh and Ang Mo Kio.

With the much vibrant colours and facades, the design of these #HDB blocks differs from those in the latter mentioned two.

The development of Bishan as a housing estate begun in 1980s and prior to that, this area was known for Kwong Wai Siew Peck San Theng, a cemetery that mainly served the Cantonese and Hakka communities of Singapore, according to Wikipedia.

Once filled with coconut plantations and used as a weekend retreat by wealthy city dwellers, Katong developed into a residential suburb by the early 20th century. It became populated by a growing English-educated middle class, including Peranakans* and Eurasians.
。
The neighbouring Joo Chiat area is named after Chew Joo Chiat, a wealthy Chinese landowner in the early 20th century. The area’s identity is especially shaped by its unique pre-war architecture – colourful two-storey shophouses and terrace houses with ornate facades, intricate motifs and ceramic tiles.
。
*The term is an Indonesian/Malay word that means “local born”, which generally refers to people of Chinese and Malay/Indonesian heritage.
。
。

Punggol Waterview View - Reflection of kelong inspired housing by Punggol Waterway

Waterview view is a distinctive HDB housing project that is inspired by the estate’s early beginning as a "kelong", or fishing village.  The blocks’ textured face mimics wood and their outdoor decks column resemble stilts of a kelong. At the same time it features  bioswales, bioretention ponds, and other water-sensitive urban design techniques with the waterway.   This housing project blends in beautifully with the waterway and features especially during the blue hour.

Trithemis aurora, the crimson marsh glider, is a species of #dragonfly in the family Libellulidae. It is a medium-sized dragonfly that is commonly found in weedy tanks and ponds, marshes, channels, and slow flowing streams and rivers in the lowlands and mid-hills. It breeds in streams, rivers, canals, ponds and tanks. (Source: Wikipedia)

post_caption:
When I accidentally dress like my surroundings (part 2).

Chanced upon this row Peranakan shophouses just next to the bustling East Coast Road. This area - Joo Chiat/Katong - is fast becoming my favourite place to explore. Having been here thrice in the last month, especially when I live at the other end of Singapore, should be a testament to Joo Chiat/Katong’s allure.

Aside from photographing these well-preserved Peranakan houses, this area has a plethora of good food! There’s famous shops selling almost every dish that’s representative of Singapore, with my favourite being “Delicious Boneless Chicken Rice” at Katong Shopping Centre.

While it’s debatable whether chicken rice is a national dish, there’s definitely no debate that eating is our national past time. Couple that with a stroll within this historic precinct will make anyone’s experience a truly local one!

Sajeev Digital Studio is more than a photography studio. Taken by Mr K Sajeev Lal, these photographs perform an important social function: they help South Asian male migrant workers find love back home in India and Sri Lanka! Mr Sajeev happily claims that he has a success rate of 100% 😉
.
An affable and jovial soul, Mr Sajeev gave me a tour of his studio and shared his personal story. I learned that he taught himself photography on a Yashica film camera when he was 15. He learnt film developing later, and adroitly turned his passion into a profession. I’m also glad that Mr Sajeev was game enough to pose for my photographs. As a photographer, I know that willing subjects are hard to come by. Mr Sajeev’s willingness made the photo-taking experience so much more fun and imbued deeper meaning into these photographs that you see here.
.
One more thing that stood out for me was the thousands of portraits of migrant workers the adorned the walls of the little studio. These portraits formed an eclectic mosaic of untold stories. I took a moment to appreciate the fact that much of Singapore’s modern development would have been impossible without them, and that they too have suffered greatly because of the coronavirus. Looking at these portraits turned out to be a gentle reminder that we can do more to appreciate our migrant workers in our midst. I realised that rediscovering Singapore is not just about visiting local places of interest because we can’t go overseas – it’s about rediscovering the different threads that form our magnificent social fabric, and how it is up to each and every one of us to make it stronger.
.

The Ice-Cream Street Hawker.🍦
Ice-cream carts like this can be found in housing estates, along Orchard Road or in the town area. They have become part of Singapore’s hawker culture and heritage. However, since their licenses are personal to the holder and non-transferable, and new ones are no longer issued anymore, we may one day see this unique trade disappear.
The ice-cream uncle here was having a snack before the customers came over, which explains why he didn’t have his mask on. 😷

Buddha Relic Tooth Temple

"Rediscover and appreciating one of the hidden beauty and gem of Singapore. Such a beautiful and magnificent structure"

This Tang-styled Chinese Buddhist temple is located in the historic district of Chinatown, Singapore. It has richly designed interiors and comprehensive exhibits on Buddhist art and history which tell stories of culture over thousands of years old. The building’s design was inspired by the Buddhist Mandala, a symbol of Buddhist culture that represents the universe.

Singapore as we all know is a place rich in culture with people still embracing the principles and beliefs passed to them through generations. Prayer is an integral part of the their culture - regardless of what religion you are in. Temples are found all over Singapore and their distinct beauty shines through despite being surrounded by modern buildings. It is a place of worship and where people spend time with their loved ones such as offering incense and attend meditations. Visiting these temples will help you to understand and experience the culture and beliefs of the people In Singapore. 

#shotoniphone

Sembawang is one of the few places in Singapore that unless you live there, you will not make a trip over. Besides the only Hot Spring in Singapore, Sembawang park is worth a visit too.

Sometimes we can see people spreading fishing net over the sea, a sight seldom see nowadays. Within the park there's Beaulieu House which is built in 1910s, now a Chinese Seafood restaurant?

It's a small park, but there are places like a  Kampong style mosque,  cycling paths, a Peranakan restaurant within landed properties, colonial houses, etc.

Nine Emperor Gods Festival 2020
龍南殿九皇大二帝爷千秋
九月初🗓🙏🙏🙏

The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia.

Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. 

This year the festival has scaled down considerably due to the Covid pandemic. Devotees, however, are still welcome to pray to the dieties but have to observe the social distancing measures in the temples.

Mini Bath Tubs
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

According to local geologists, the exact source of the spring remains unknown, but it is believed that its origin may be southwest of its actual location, possibly at Bukit Timah. Hot springs are formed when underground water comes into contact with hot rock masses. The resulting high pressure causes the water to seep upwards through cracks, forcing itself out of the ground as a spring.

A series of tests conducted by the PSB Corporation and SGS Testing & Control Services found the spring water contains 420 mg of chloride per litre, an amount which is substantially higher than the 35 to 100 mg in the water from Choa Chu Kang & Bedok waterworks. It was also found that the sulphide content is three times more than tap water & the spring water is also slightly alkaline due to the presence of minerals. Natural spring waters may have health benefits, similar to the hot springs of other countries near tectonic plates with volcanoes, in a search for cures for some skin conditions, as well as debilitating ailments like rheumatism & arthritis. Although local rheumatologists conceded that hydrotherapy is an accepted treatment that can be helpful for mild forms of rheumatism or muscle strain, they, along with dermatologists, remain skeptical of claims about the alternative healing of the natural spring water.

Hot hard water bubbles continuously in the well, releasing a slightly unpleasant sulphur mud-like odour together with steam. The temperature of the spring water is measured by precision instrument to be constant 70 °C (160 °F). In an investigation carried out by the Nanyang Technological University in 1994, the hot spring was found to have an estimated yield of approximately 150 litres (33 imp gal; 40 US gal) per minute at ground level through installed steel casings.

post_caption:
Me the local tourist returned to childhood. 

This place reminds me of the kopithiam (not the brand: kopithiam that ruined the traditional image) that my grandfather brought me to when I was a kiddo. I was forced to drink milo off the saucer while he enjoyed his coffee with a piece of gu you in it! WHY CAN I HAVE GU YOU IN MY MILO? 

I can’t remember when is the last time I have gu you in my coffee and my bet was more than a decade, or two. 

I wish I had seated closer to the uncle and mesmerise his act of this traditional trade. 

I want to go back again, and again, and again. 

Who else wanna join me?

post_caption:
Who else starts the week already thinking about the next weekend? 🙋‍♀️😂 I think we'll spend a day in Pulau Ubin as Nic couldn't make it last time, I can't wait to show him around the island! #SeteMilKmEmSingapura⠀
⠀
Pulau Ubin is one of the 64 islands/islets that make up Singapore and a welcome tropical getaway if you want to escape the city for a day. The once bustling island used to be explored for its granite - Pulau Ubin actually means "Granite Island" in Malay - but nowadays the abandoned quarries have turned into lakes and less than 50 people live there.⠀
⠀
Hiking, biking, swimming, kayaking (and of course taking pictures 😂), Pulau Ubin has lots to offer just a 10 minute boat ride away. There are also bike rentals, little shops and restaurants owned by the locals - probably the last witnesses of the Singaporean way of life prior to the country's fast modernisation.⠀
⠀
📸 Shot with the help of my hiking buddy @blondiewanderlust ⠀
⠀
⠀
🇧🇷 Quem também começa a segunda já planejando o final de semana? 🙋‍♀️😂 Acho que vamos passar um dia em Pulau Ubin já que Nic não pôde ir quando eu fui, quero tanto mostrar a ilha pra ele!⠀
⠀
Pulau Ubin é uma das 64 ilhas/ilhotas que formam Singapura e uma ótima pedida pra quem quer fugir da cidade por um tempinho. A ilha era explorada pelo seu granito - por isso o nome Pulau Ubin, "Ilha de Granito" em malaio! - mas hoje em dia as antigas pedreiras se transformaram em lagos e menos de 50 pessoas moram na ilha.⠀
⠀
Trilha, ciclismo, passeio de caiaque (e claro, tirar muitas fotos 😂), Pulau Ubin tem muito a oferecer a apenas 10 minutinhos de barco da ilha principal. Também tem onde alugar bicicleta, lojinhas e restaurantes administrados pelos locais - provavelmente os últimos guardiões do antigo estilo de vida comum antes da modernização de Singapura.
Blessed with great weather over the weekends - happy Monday everyone!

This cluster of HDB blocks at Balam Road were built between 1967 and 1973. A few years ago, they were given a new coat of paint and I love how they stand out with their red, yellow and blue façade, inspired by Dutch Modernist painter Piet Mondrain’s 1930 painting, “Composition with Red, Blue and Yellow” among the newer blocks in the same vicinity. Those trees in the midst also provide shade and bring some greenery to the surroundings.

I’m glad many of us in Singapore are fortunate to have a roof over our heads and stay safe especially during this COVID-19 pandemic.

post_caption:
Almost 8 years ago i told myself that i would only want a child when i am ready.. ⁣
⁣
Oh well to be honest no matter how prepared you are, you’ll be left unprepared still, there are so many new things to learn and so many things to deal with physically and mentally.. ⁣
I could totally get it when someone said they do not want a child, it’s personal choice.. ⁣
⁣
But don’t get me wrong.. At one point i really want a child.. and till now never ever regretting to have one on my own.. ⁣
Even though, life is getting more tough and harder now.. I feel life more fulfilling and purposeful.. Motherhood is the greatest thing and the hardest thing.. At the end of the day, i am going to raise a human being..⁣
⁣
To all struggling mommies, let’s think in this postive way: if today was rough and i feel that i am not good enough, i’ll try again tomorrow.. 💪🏻

Nine Emperor Gods Festival 2020
@ Leong Nam Temple 
龍南殿九皇大二帝爷圣诞 
Rain or shine...devotees come in drove to offer prayers to the Nine Emperor Gods.
The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia. 
Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. Today, the younger generations have taken an interest in the festival, with many youths taking part in the processions. Involving the younger generations allows us to continue this intangible cultural heritage for many generations to come.

post_caption:
Home! 

Bishan-Ang Mo Kio Park is one of the largest parks in Singapore. Built in 1988,1 the park was revamped between 2009 and 2011 under the Active, Beautiful, Clean Waters (ABC Waters) Programme launched by PUB, Singapore’s National Water Agency.

 Subsequently, the park was reopened in 2012. Spanning 62 ha, it stretches along Ang Mo Kio Avenue 1 from Upper Thomson Road to Bishan Road.
An iconic feature of Bishan-Ang Mo Kio Park is the naturalised river meandering through it. The three-kilometre waterway was converted from a concrete canal that channelled the Kallang River at the edge of the park. 

When the water level in the river is low, visitors can walk down the gentle river banks to get closer to the water; but during heavy rain, the parkland next to the river doubles up as a conveyance channel and carries excess water downstream.

Concrete slabs from the original canal have been stacked up to create a mound called Recycle Hill. An award-winning sculpture by Kelvin Lim Fun Kit titled An Enclosure for a Swing can be found at the top of the hill, where visitors can enjoy a good view of the entire park.

This building along #ToaPayoh Lorong Two is the headquarters of Singapore Federation of Chinese Clan Associations (SFCCA) since 1997. 

Prior to that, this premises used to belong to Heng A Khe Bong #School, a primary school that started in 1973 but traced its roots to two separate institutions - Heng A School (founded in 1918) and Khe Bong School (in 1920).

The two schools came together and stayed together before it closed down in 1993.

Retired birds from @jurongbirdpark.sg Kings of the Skies show will now enjoy the rest of their golden years in a new aviary open to the public. 🤗

The oldest resident at the senior aviary is Rod Stewart (first slide), an Egyptian vulture who is estimated to have hatched in the early 1960s making him close to 60 years old. With an average of 21-year lifespan for this species in the wild, Rod has lived way beyond his life expectancy and is said to remain “spritely for his age and likes to roam about the ground level of the exhibit.”

Check out the Marina Bay Sands SkyPark Observation Deck vlog.

Located 57 storeys up from the heart of the Marina Bay area, the Sands SkyPark Observation Deck boasts scenic views of the panoramic vistas of Marina Bay and Singapore’s world-class cityscape. Take in a bird’s-eye view of Gardens by the Bay and the impressive Supertree Grove, or admire the sea view that stretches from Marina South Pier to the Singapore Strait.

Hoe Nam Prawn Noodles, because @pennysnoops wanted to have good prawn noodles with pig intestines. This one is so well known that every Grab driver we rode with knew about the fabled noodles for supper, and the bad serving attitude that comes with it! 

You can see how it's like 57 flavors of Baskin Robbins, savoury edition, as you can load your noodles with pork ribs, clams, small or big prawns, and much more. 

To me it's all about the broth, and this one is not bad, though I still prefer the mega prawn noodles at Zion Road Food Centre where the broth has more kick. 

Anyway this neighborhood has a lot of interesting eats, and the condos here all look damn nice. We had ice cream and waffles after dinner from #SweetCheeks and spotted a Turtle Soup restaurant which is a little hardcore for us. 🔥

"Kampong life"
The Last Kampong in Singapore - Appreciate that the last kampong on Singapore’s mainland, not only does Lorong Buangkok serve as an important cultural and historical symbol, I feel that its camaraderie is also something that we can learn from. Residents there welcome each other’s presence and help each other out.
Even though HDB flats attempt to imitate the kampong spirit and induce cohesion among the residents, the camaraderie present is but only a feeble imitation of the kampong spirit.

Kampong Buangkok’s postal code was 1954, when Singapore still used only four digits for postal codes before 1st September 1995. It has since been changed to a six-digit postal code now, but this sign remains as a nostalgic reminder. There's always a sense of warmth and presence of human touch in such a peaceful environment like how friendly Mak Cik (malay auntie) was when I chatted with her. 
Hope this place will be kept and allow the younger generations to learn those valuable lessons we can never learn in class.

Remember to seek Mr and Miss Sng for approval to walk through this wonderful kampong. Seek the residents permission and respect the residents' privacy when are in their premises.

<364> 《走入时光隧道》

这是一条时光隧道。不信你试试看。

在时隔多年以后，我今早再次步入这一条从马林百列镇中心通往东海岸公园的地下人行通道。我人还没走出地道，便满满的青春回忆涌上心头。

还记得，你曾和朋友们结伴到东海岸，一起骑脚踏车、一起烤肉、一起唱歌、一起看海聊天、直到天明吗？还记得，那时候，谁和妳是如影随形的朋友吗？还记得，既期待自己也能碰上喜欢的人，又羡慕地看着谁和谁在一起了吗？这都是何其宝贵的青春回忆呀！

想回味的话，请进入这一条时光隧道吧！

<364> “Walking Into A Time Tunnel" 

This is a time tunnel. Try it, if you do not believe me.

After many years, I once again set foot on this underground walkway from Marine Parade town center to East Coast Park this morning. Before I got out of the tunnel, many memories from my youthful years were erupting. 

Do you remember yourself going to the East Coast Park with your friends together to ride bicycles, barbecue food, sing songs, watch the sea and chat ‘till dawn? Do you also remember the friend who was always sticking with you? And do you remember how you yearned to be with someone you like, while looking at your friends who had found someone they loved with envy? Those were the precious memories of youth!

If you would like to relive those memories, I suggest that you enter this time tunnel! 

<364> “Shíguāng suìdào”

Zhè shì yītiáo shíguāng suìdào. Bùxìn nǐ shì shìkàn.

Zài shí gé duōnián yǐhòu, wǒ jīn zǎo zàicì bù rù zhè yītiáo cóng mǎ lín bǎi liè zhèn zhōngxīn tōng wǎng dōng hǎi'àn gōngyuán dì dìxià rénxíng tōngdào. Wǒ rén hái méi zǒuchū dìdào, biàn mǎn mǎn de qīngchūn huíyì yǒng shàng xīntóu.

Hái jìdé, nǐ céng hé péngyǒumen jiébàn dào dōng hǎi'àn, yīqǐ qí jiǎotàchē, yīqǐ kǎoròu, yīqǐ chànggē, yīqǐ kàn hǎi liáotiān, zhídào tiānmíng ma? Hái jìdé, nà shíhòu, shéi hé nǎi shì rúyǐngsuíxíng de péngyǒu ma? Hái jìdé, jì qídài zìjǐ yě néng pèng shàng xǐhuān de rén, yòu xiànmù de kànzhe shéi hé shéi zài yīqǐle ma? Zhè dōu shì héqí bǎoguì de qīngchūn huíyì ya!

Xiǎng huíwèi dehuà, qǐng jìnrù zhè yītiáo shíguāng suìdào bà!

post_caption:
Shopping for Natural Spring Water
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

During its peak, up to 300 people visited the hot spring daily. On 1 March 2002, it was closed for two months while upgrading & improvement works were carried out to the area around the spring, which had become sodden & muddy. Littering had also become a problem because of the increased numbers of visitors. The former dirt track leading to the spring was paved with cement, & lined with bougainvillea bushes & high fences to ensure the security of the air base. Drainage pipes were also installed. Mindef, which owns the land, allows public access between 7 am and 7 pm daily, free-of-charge. When the spring reopened on 1 May 2002, more than 100 people visited the site despite the afternoon drizzle. At the same time, some new free-hold condominiums were built in the surrounding area; one of the developments, built by the property arm of F&N in 2001, is called Seletaris, named after the company's former mineral water.

In July 2005, a Business Times reader proposed that the authorities should explore the possibility of tapping the geothermal heat that lies many miles under Sembawang—similar to the project in South Australia's Cooper Basin—in order to aid Singapore's reliance on oil and gas. The proposal was not acted upon.

 As of 2014, the well can still be seen locked inside a red-brick enclosure with a steel gate, & its geothermal heat can be felt outside the building. Some plastic chairs, pails and mini-tubs kindly donated by visitors are stored at the perimeter of the compound, which has a makeshift shed in one corner. A caretaker, paid for by Mindef, takes care of the place to maintain its overall cleanliness, but there is no toilet on location. The hot spring is less frequented nowadays but remains rustic for rural & suburban families to discover & explore.

Old & New
Toa Payoh Lorong 6 Dragon Playground
(Singapore Heritage)

The dragon-shaped sand-based playground used to be a popular design for playgrounds in Ang Mo Kio and Toa Payoh.

After 1993, they were phased out due to safety concerns and it is believed that this Dragon Playground of Toa Payoh (located at Blk 28 Toa Payoh Lorong 6) is the only one of its kinds (sand-based) left in Singapore (The other two are laid with rubber mats).

The dragon playground was designed in 1979 by Housing and  Development Board’s (HDB) in-house designer Khor Ean Ghee (born 1935), who got his inspiration from the Oriental dragon commonly seen among the Chinese community in Singapore.

Beside the majestic dragon, there are two little plastic rides in the shapes of a seahorse and a pony for children to sit on.

The long body of the dragon is made of steel rails which form a passage for kids to get to the dragon head. Using the slide, kids can descend from the dragon head to the sandy ground.

The Toa Payoh dragon playground was picked by New York culture blog, Flavorwire.com, in 2013 as one of 15 amazing playgrounds from all over the world.

HDB Toa Payoh Apex (Background):

HDB Toa Payoh Apex is bounded by Lorong 6 Toa Payoh and Toa Payoh East, approximately 10 minutes (1.1km) walk away from Toa Payoh MRT Station. 

This development consist of 557 units of 3- and 4-room Standard Flats. All 4 blocks of flats come with three-quarter height windows in the living/ dining area and half-height windows in other rooms. Highest floor is 36 storey.

Chinatown Singapore Mid-Autumn Festival Lightup 2020.
Rain or shine, covid or not, the Mid-Autumn Festival @chinatown_festivals is on.  Kudos to the organisers for lighting up Chinatown to bring some festive cheers to the sombre mood brought about by the pandemic.  Although the hustle and bustle of night markets is missing, lesser crowd allows people to enjoy the colourful lanterns lightup more.

Pinnacle@Duxton is a public housing project at 1A Cantonment Road. It is the first 50-storey public housing project in Singapore, and also the first in the world with two sky bridges linking seven towers. The sky bridges create two layers of sky parks that offer panoramic views of the city. Resulting from the first international competition for public housing in Singapore, Pinnacle@Duxton is regarded as groundbreaking for redefining the concept of public housing with its unique design features.

As a West-sider, the Eastern part of Singapore is somewhere I rarely step foot into. A month back, while visiting a friend in the east, I decided to explore Joo Chiat/Katong area - Singapore’s first Heritage Town. 

Since then, I’ve returned twice more to check off a handful of must-eats there, and to hunt down Instagrammable spots like these unique pre-war shophouses.

Moments like this make me think about the upside of being trapped in Singapore (although not indefinitely). I’m “forced” to rediscover my country, which brings along opportunities to learn about and view this little red dot through a different lens. Can’t wait to check out more sights & makan places around Singapore , and looking forward to playing host to foreign friends again when leisure travel resumes!

Dealing with green is quite challenging.
Sometimes green in nature is overly vibrant. I sometimes reduce its intensity by lowering the saturation or by increasing its brightness. I could also shift its hue slightly to either yellow or aqua. Or I can reduce the contrast of the entire image so you can reduce the overall “power” of the image. In any ways, the decisions are hugely influenced by the existence of the green. This time I tried to weaken the presence of the green by strengthen the power of red to counter (opposite color hue). I achieved the aged old photo look accidentally. Very interesting experiment.

The Baobabs, Flower Dome
5 October - 1 November

Make your way into an urban oasis and take respite amidst the luscious shades of green and sweet floral scents.

The sight of the brilliantly coloured macaws instantly captures our attention, as do the beautiful blooms of the bamboo orchid, a native species that is used extensively in the landscapes of our metropolitan city-state. Man is innately attracted to nature and seeks to make connections with other life forms. This affinity with the natural world is known as “biophilia”, meaning “a love of life” in Greek.

The transformation from a Garden City to City in a Garden and the movement towards City in Nature have seen the integration of biophilic design into our concrete jungle. Treelined streets, skyrise greenery and world-class gardens and parks that teem with a diversity of flora and fauna are a reflection of how Singapore has successfully incorporated nature and its ecosystem into the urban fabric, integrating both harmoniously. These efforts have not only increased biodiversity in the city, but also influenced the way we work and play.

Redesign your work and living spaces by simply introducing some plants! Beyond their aesthetic value, plants also create a restorative environment to engage our senses, promote emotional and mental well-being, and boost productivity. Jam-packed with design and therapeutic benefits, it is no surprise that many have been drawn to nurture their green fingers whilst working from home! If you’re new to introducing nature to your home or workspace, a good starter option would be the air plant, a low maintenance houseplant that can be used as a table centrepiece or hanging ornament. Alternatively, the use of cut flowers like the exotic birds of paradise seen on display can liven up your space effortlessly!

Chilli crab, Hokkaido scallops, tiger prawns — Singaporeans are sure no strangers to seafood! But ever wonder where some of your favourite restaurants get their seafood from?

Membina 118 have Block 118A, 118B, 118C & 118D at Jalan Membina are 30 storey HDB public housing flats in Bukit Merah, District 03, Singapore. It has a total of 172 units with 172 units of 4-room unit type in every block. These flats were completed in 2001 and has a 80 years lease remaining.

🇸🇬 2020 CAN STILL BE YOUR YEAR! 🇸🇬
𝗬𝗼𝘂 𝗸𝗻𝗼𝘄 𝘄𝗵𝗲𝗻 𝗮 𝗻𝗲𝘄 𝘆𝗲𝗮𝗿 𝗮𝗿𝗿𝗶𝘃𝗲𝘀, 𝘆𝗼𝘂 𝗼𝗳𝘁𝗲𝗻 𝘀𝗮𝘆 “𝘁𝗵𝗶𝘀 𝗶𝘀 𝗺𝘆 𝘆𝗲𝗮𝗿“ ... 𝗪𝗲𝗹𝗹 𝗶𝘁 𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗹𝗹 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲!
Instead of focusing on the things that don't matter, get obsessed with who you're becoming, where you're going and all of the amazing things you're going to accomplish!

More than ever, this year in which everything has been on pause, has been the best time to do everything you always wanted to do! Your personal projects, your side-hustles, etc!

To think that there is only 3 months left to this year is crazy, but don’t let that time pass by, use it wisely and create!

It has been such a year, not much travel, but on a positive side, I got to see so much more of what Singapore has to offer, to create great friendships and have many wonderful projects involving talented people.

Hope that you got the chance to optimize this weird 2020 as well and celebrate little wins!

If you a fan of traditional kopitiam that has not only traditionally brewed authentic coffee aroma but also an old uncle complete in his iconic blue-strip pyjamas, then this time-stood-still coffee shop is for you.  Toasted bread are done over charcoal fire and coffee are done pouring in and out of the brownish-stained coffee bag.  There is even a good olden day timber counter that is no longer used by a cashier, but are stack with traditional biscuits and cookies kept in containers that appear to be used since day one.  If Singapore is serious about preserving its food culture, then this shop has to be gazetted for its intangible cultural heritage that dated back to the 60s and 70s

post_caption:
You want to get started with night photography but not to spend that long 4 hours. 

I get it !

So I came up with a 2 hours workshop

What we’ll do... 

I’ll coach you the basic elements of night photography, providing you with tips and techniques of low light and long exposure photography. 

We will be working on camera settings to create different effects to capture fascinating images as the day changes from twilight hour into the night. 

What you’ll get...

At the end of the workshop, you will acquire the knowledge to capture light trails, to create the effect of light burst and silky waters, creating stunning colour tones to your night images as well as capturing modern and historical architecture illuminated with colourful lights that adorned the cityscape.

No filter required!

Just practical stuff from your in-camera settings.

Where we’ll be...

This workshop takes place at one of Singapore's most vibrant quays along the Singapore River, within a vicinity that is surrounded by historical and modern architecture. 

The location provides you with all the required subjects of interest to photograph in low light and to acquire the skills of night photography.

What others said....

Don’t just hear this from me. 

Swipe to your left to read what participant has to say about this workshop.

All that for $120 per person.

And that’s not the end of us...

I keep the communication channel open for all my workshops’ past and present participants. 

Participants still text or email me from time to time, checking in on unclear camera setups, asking for opinions and reviews of their work. 

Book your spot through info@carolinepang.com

Commuting by public transport again recently.. Appreciating those ME time moments on my way back and forth daily..⁣
⁣
Do you realize art galore happening at almost every MRT station in Singapore?⁣
⁣
And this is one of them.. ⁣
At Newton station, the artist created a monochrome drawing of the area in year 2200. The 11m by 9m picture forms the backdrop to the station's escalators and commuters can marvel at the artist imagined city, comprising layers of stacked buildings with snaking highways.⁣
⁣
Don’t you love that crossing escalator with art at the background? To be honest it was very easy to take this photo with zero human traffic at escalator, just need to wait for the off-peak timing in between train arrival.⁣
⁣
Which one is your favourite MRT station in Singapore?

📍 Newton MRT (Downtown Line) ⁣

First geocache - Easter Egg [GC8T562]
🗝 They always say - first step is the hardest. 

So, we take a baby step to start an adventure. 

09Oct2020 (Pandemic ~ Covid19 🦠) That was D day - Children’s Day, a School holiday in Singapore. Probably the best reason to not we procrastinate any further. 

We decided to get out and explore this day with E, our daughter, instead of coping at home studying and mugging for exams. Mugging a word often used for Singaporean children to go on drilling for their exams. 😄Muggle used in #harrypotter to describe someone who doesn’t know anything related magic and the wizardry world. Often used in Singapore to describe anyone who is not geocaching. 🤣 

Ok I went off-point. 

🗒 We started with a short walk along the footpath towards the treasure following the description. Surrounded by overgrown creepy green leaves, it took us about ten minutes (normal pace) to reach the coordinates. 

Walking with masks in this horrible humidity and heat was another challenge. 

This, however, did not deter E’s enthusiasm. She loves treasure hunting and detective stories. #geocaching will be the best family bonding activity, well, a family hobby. Besides, we had a pretty heavy lunch (steamboat/ hotpot!), so it was time to walk it off. 🤗

Soon we reached the exact spot but we just cannot find it!

Trying to clear some soil by rubbing our shoes on the ground, yes(!) we are neat freaks and too virus conscious nowadays. Everything seemed to have a layer of germs on it. 🤪

After fifteen minutes of poking and brushing the tips of the grass with my slippers, we decided to message the owner of the cache.

Funnily enough, while waiting for the reply, G being the man as he always is, decided to dig into some suspicious ground and found the Yellow Egg! It was a lovely “Easter-egg” Hunt! 🥳 

We are grateful to find our first cache in this little adventure of our mundane life. 🙏🏻 looking forward to more little hunts in the future. 

Meanwhile, stay safe and mask on! 😷

Take a walk around the estates of Adam Park and Alexandra Park, and be brought back to the Singapore of a different time. Admire the splendour of British colonial houses and their unique black and white characteristics, set within lush greenery, that paved way to an unrivalled architecture legacy in the region. You might just rediscover snippets of forgotten stories or surprise yourself with the history these houses hold and tell.⁠
⁠
You may even get the rare chance to visit a Black & White home, along with a private viewing of the owner’s collection of interesting antiques and curios over the years. Soak in the ambience, chat and socialise over tea and treats. 🍵⁠
⁠
Who would you like to take on your time travelling journey? 🚀 Share with us in the comments below.

Rojak Flower / Torch Ginger Flower / Bunga Kantan. Delighted to see it again. It used to grow in our garden and mom would simply add it to a dinner salad. Finely julienned, a whisper of it  adds a distinct floral note to our local hawker favourite Rojak. If the Rojak man didn't display it in his store window, Auntie F would refuse to order it. It's also used in Penang Assam Laksa, which if you're lucky enough to have the real thing, is one of the most umami loaded seafood briny noodle soup we know of.

I missed Kampong.

SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Kampong Lorong Buangkok

Kampong Lorong Buangkok is a village located in Buangkok in Hougang, Singapore. Built in 1956, it is the last surviving kampong located on Singapore Island.

Decide to do a local tour there and I met with some very friendly folks there and one even invited me to their home for a chat.

The kampong village retains the rustic beauty and it reminded me of my kampong childhood, living in my grandfather's house in Chua Chu Kang.

The kids here run freely and the  folks here are always obliging for a chat and phototaking, which is true in the kampong spirit.

You can see herbs, mango trees and even coca plant.

Along the way, we met some visitors who brought their kids to learn more about our traditional kampong heritage.

This is certainly an enjoyable  trip and would suggests everyone to experience kampong lifestyle.

Travel photography is not just about shooting nice places or destinations or good food. 

It is about connecting viewers to the uniqueness of the place, it’s people, it’s culture and nature. 

It is a powerful tool to create awareness of cross cultural exchanges and many more that you can achieve through travel photography. 

It is beyond camera settings and filters.

Those are the fundamentals that I will share in my travel photography workshops and coach  potential photography participants who want to learn more on travel and documentary photography.

What is travel photography to you?

Before you sign up for any of my workshops, I encourage you to read, not just reviews on my workshops, but my works as a Travel and Documentary photographer to see whether my expertise and workshops match your requirements:

Shooting For A Change - 
https://singaporemagazine.sif.org.sg/shooting-for-a-change

My Life As A Travel & Documentary Photographer - 
https://www.asiaone.com/travel/singaporean-photographer-sacrifices-stable-pay-lux-living-hot-showers-get-close-locals

For no particular reason, this time I was listening to ‘It’s Beginning to Look a Lot Like Christmas’ by Michael Bublé and I still get this sad ass photos.
I thought I was feeling happy while listening to the song.
But I guess my soul can’t help but show its true color as you can see in the photo. 
I guess I don’t even need those sad songs to be sad because Ima sad ass bitch by heart.
Or I guess ‘Christmas’ in my heart is more like ‘Merry Christmas, Mr. Lawrence’ Christmas.

The colourful Alkaff Bridge at Robertson Quay in Singapore.

Built in 1997 in the shape of a  tongkang—a light boat that shipped goods along the river—this 55-metre- the long pedestrian bridge was named after a prominent family who lived in  Singapore in the early 20th century. In 2004,  Filipino artist Pacita Abad painted it with whimsical patterns using 55 colours. This artwork is also one of The artist’s final projects.

Shot on Nikon Z5 + NIKKOR Z 24-200mm f/4-6.3 VR lens. By @javan

168A 🦋🦋🦋

Before the Butterfly Block was constructed, early HDB residential blocks were largely designed as simple slab blocks and point blocks as the focus then was to build efficiently. With its unique curves and aesthetic façade, the Butterfly Block is an effort to create more variety and character in public housing estates through innovative designs.

Paul Fernandez (b. 1940) and his family moved into the Butterfly Block in 1975. He recalled, “There was a circular carriage way, Rumah Bomba (Malay: Fire House) Circus, at the end of the Butterfly Block where the itinerant hawkers would set up their food stalls. The firefighters from Alexandra Fire Station and the expatriates from Gillman Barracks would frequent the food stalls.”

We always work for a better tomorrow. But when tomorrow comes, instead of enjoying, we again think of a better tomorrow. Let’s have a better today.

What a view of Clementi❤️
13 Oct 2020
Clementi is named after Sir Cecil Clementi Smith, the Governor of the Straits Settlement from 1887 to 1893. Part of Clementi used to be swamp land. The other part was made up of kampungs and villages with squatter-type homes, backyard trades, cottage industries, and farms.

As one of the earliest HDB towns, Clementi’s development took place in the 1970s with plans for the town to be self-sufficient and support an adequate range of facilities and services with job opportunities to meet various social and economic needs.

Clementi has grown from its humble beginnings into a vibrant and popular estate. The town is also known for the many tertiary educational institutions located there, including Ngee Ann Polytechnic, Singapore Polytechnic, and the National University of Singapore.

Few weeks ago I followed @andy1um, @izmyphotos, @victorl0 and @photographyholic to the peranakan houses in Joo Chiat. It was a bright day... why these people love to roast me under the over-excited sun during a photowalk ah? 😅

Not sure if you notice; because of the fengshui, peranakan houses are designed symmetrically with entrance located in the centre flanked by windows on the both sides. It’s also common to have Chinese inscribed signboard hung above the main door as well as ventilation openings carved in wood with symbolic decorations.

On Koon Seng Rd, Joo Chiat, you can find the bat-shaped ventilations which actually symbolize Good Luck. Here is something I’m very sure you didn’t notice until now; swipe to see a close-up, spot the bat-shaped ventilations and compare it with the logo of @stb_sg 😉

Warehouse
.
.
.
.

The Warehouse Hotel was built in 1895 along the Singapore River as part of the Straits of Malacca trade route. At that time, the area was a hotbed of secret societies, underground activity, and liquor distilleries. Today, while much of that history has disappeared, The Warehouse Hotel has been meticulously restored as a modern 37-room boutique hotel, focusing on heritage and local culture.

Day 2 #BalloInSingapore 
I did not know we had such amazing hiking trails within Singapore till few of my friends(Shuchi Kapoor  Seema Balani) decided to explore the place . It was love at first sight when I looked at the pics and I decided that it was my next destination in Singapore to explore.
 MacRitchie reservoir is a place to enjoy tranquility if walking above a lush green foliage.I bumped into monkeys, monitor lizard and squirrels .
Macritchie can be termed Singaporean cousin of famous Cloud forest trail in Laos.
A must visit place says Ballo  either early in morning or evening ( before sunset) with your friends and family .

Today is the last day to join us for the #SingapoRediscovers photography contest in collaboration with Singapore Tourism Board!

All you have to do is to check out our itinerary (link in bio), visit at least 2 of the 6 precincts featured and share at least 2 original shots captured in your own style. We’ve included example photo spots in the itinerary, but your photos can be captured at other spots as well! These can be carousel-style posts or separate posts.

3 steps to take part in the contest:
1. Share with us what rediscovering Singapore means to you in the post caption
2. Follow @sgig and @stb_sg on Instagram
3, Hashtag #SGIGRediscovers #SingapoRediscovers.

You will stand a chance to win the following attractive prizes:

1st Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Marina Bay Sands (worth over SGD $339)
2nd Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Mandarin Orchard Singapore (worth over SGD $280)
3rd Prize: 2 x Tickets to Universal Studios Singapore (worth up to SGD $162)

Consolation Prizes:
 4th, 5th, 6th, 7th prizes: 4 x #InstaWalk Bugis, Waterloo and Kampong Gelam Tribe Tours (worth $55 per ticket)
8th, 9th and 10th prizes: 3 x Tickets to Trick Eye Museum Singapore (worth up to $25 per ticket)

For more info on the contest and its T&Cs, please click on the link in bio.

| From dust to dust
• Sony a6000 + SEL55210 •

Did you know that the lush lawn in front of the Fort Canning Centre used to be a Christian cemetery? One can hardly tell when there. Despite the headstones on the side, there is a calm serenity on the lawn as people lay out their mats for picnics and kids run around playing catch. 

"Developed in 1822 by George Coleman – Singapore’s first architect and Stamford Raffles’ consultant on the first Town Plan – the Fort Canning Christian cemetery had approximately 600 graves interred. 

The cemetery was eventually closed in 1865, and the state of the burial grounds began to deteriorate. In 1953, the City Council exhumed the cemetery and created a “Garden of Memory”."

Some of the headstones have been incorporated into a beautiful brick wall that runs down the sloping hill.

<359> “Have You Seen Any Crocodile?” 

Daunted by the inaccessibility of public transport and the fear of mosquito bites in a swampy forest, I had avoided visiting Sungei Buloh Wetland for a long time. 

Today, I was delighted to discover a new entrance to the wetland at Kranji Reservoir. And it was a pleasure to walk above the mudflat by crossing a suspension bridge and a coastal boardwalk. Thankfully, too, there were no mosquitoes today! Rather, there were butterflies and birds.

A passer-by asked me, looking disappointed, “I see many signboards cautioning about crocodiles. But I spotted none so far. Had you seen a crocodile?”

Bemused by his question, I shook my head and let out a laugh. 

William

<361> “Do you know where to look for eagles?”

Do you know there is a place to watch eagles 🦅 flying in the skies? 

I was searching high up for eagles through an circular structure situated at the end of the boardwalk. The blue sky was unbelievably beautiful filled with thin layers of clouds, but there was no sight of any eagle.

Surely there must be eagles in this place known as the Eagle Point at Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve. So I set my sights further and lower.  There, an eagle was swooping down close to the sea as if it was hunting for fish.  But it was too far for my phone camera to capture a close-up. Perhaps, I should really get myself a better camera one day. 

Still, I was delighted to catch a glimpse of an eagle!

William

Karma is an action, not a result. The future is not set in stone as you can change the course of your life at this very moment by changing your intentional acts and self-destructive patterns.

Karma is energy and it’s our intentional thoughts and actions. The energy we generate now and in the future will affect us. It has nothing to do with reward or punishment. 

For us, our karma is treating life as big collaboration. Individually, we are one drop. 
Together, we are an ocean.
Daily, in your own little ways, the best we can all do is stay positive, support each other and put a smile on the face of people around. 

Kindness, Positivity, Support, Collaboration always win.
Anger, Negativity, Resentment, Jealousy ... well we don't care about the outcome as they are ignored and dismissed.

Stay positive! Keep communucating with your loved ones and we will go through this 2020 year all fine 🙏🏼

Gai gai (街街) refers to going for a leisurely walk.. ⁣⁣
It’s a word we tell @dearbbkai everytime we bring him out.. As the things started to opening up slowly and almost back to normal, we took a courage to bring baby out weekly, capturing more moments because he grows up rapidly! ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Happy to be able to witness his milestones as i still working from home for half of the week.. As you can see from IG stories now @dearbbkai able to rolls over, need to be extra cautious now.. ⁣⁣
Some of you asked me how me and hubby manage to take care newborn while working full time without any help.. We didn’t hire helper and our Moms are staying overseas, so we have no choice to take care baby on our own.. It’s not that hard to be honest, we both need to be very hands-on and have to get use do thing efficiently.. So if you are on the same situation like me, especially due to this pandemic you can’t get any help, don’t worry too much!⁣⁣
⁣⁣
📍Chijmes⁣⁣
CHIJMES (pronounced "chimes", acronym definition: Convent of the Holy Infant Jesus and ‘MES’ was added intentionally to make it sounds like chimes) is a historic building complex in Singapore.⁣
⁣⁣
The complex was used as a Catholic convent since 1852, with an acquired Caldwell House which was constructed in 1840–1841, an acquired Convent Orphanage house in 1855, the Convent of the Holy Infant Jesus Chapel in 1904 and an acquired hotel complex for the girls' school in 1933. The Caldwell House, currently a wedding venue, and the Gothic-style chapel, renamed as CHIJMES Hall, currently a function hall and also a wedding venue, have both been gazetted as national monuments. The complex has been restored in 1996 for commercial purposes as a dining, shopping and entertainment centre with ethnic restaurants, shops and a function hall, providing a backdrop for musicals, recitals, theatrical performances and weddings. (Source: Wikipedia)⁣⁣

1 Ekim 2020’de Ankara Singapur Büyükelçiliği’nde küçük bir Singapur dostu Türk grubuyla (#FriendsofSingapore) Ay Festivali (Mooncake Festival) olarak da bilinen Güz Ortası Festivali’ni (Mid-Autumn Festival) kutladık. Birbirinden lezzetli ay keklerinin tadını çıkararak Çin çayı içtik ve festivalin tarihi ile mitolojisi hakkında bilgi edindik!
.
Çok ırklı ve çok dinli bir ülke olarak, Singapur topluma farklı görüntüler, sesler, tatlar ve inançlar mozaiği sunan, geleneksel ve dini birçok festival kutlar! Güz Ortası Festivali, Çin asıllı Singapurlular tarafından kutlanan ve MÖ 1600 yılına dayanan bir festival olup, hasat zamanının başlangıcını ve Ay’ın en parlak olduğu zamanı kutlar!
.
Elçilikte yapılan kutlamanın kısa bir videosuna buradan erişebilirsiniz!
.
On 1 October 2020, we celebrated Mid-Autumn Festival or 中秋节 (also known as Mooncake Festival) at the Singapore Embassy in Ankara with a small group of Turkish #FriendsofSingapore (due to social distancing requirements). We enjoyed a variety of delicious mooncakes and Chinese tea, and learnt about the history and mythology behind the festival!
.
As a multiracial and multireligious country, Singapore celebrates a wide range of festivals – both religious and traditional, giving our society a vibrant mosaic of sights, sounds, tastes and beliefs! The Mid-Autumn Festival is celebrated by the Singaporean Chinese and is one of the oldest festivals dating back to 1600 BC. This marks the start of the harvest season and a time of year that the moon is at its brightest! 
.
Here is a short video of the celebration at the Embassy!

First timer at the hotspring. Heard its about 40 degrees at the foot dipping area, but I feel its more than that, as the hotspring source is already at 70 degrees. 

Most people dare not put their feet in entirely, because it really does feel like putting your foot in boiling water. I was hovering too initially, but got tired and decided to just plonk my feet in. Turned out it actually feels good. Sure does promote blood circulation because my feet became red like lobster after 30s of dipping. 

Take a container and some eggs along too to make some onsen eggs! 🥚🥚🥚

post_caption:
“We are going to be served Hashbrown.” Yes, you heard me right, Chef Bjorn Shen has created, what could possibly, be one of the best hashbrowns that you have ever tasted. New on the menu and to take a dig at the Golden Arches, this version of Homemade Hashbrown ($14) is made from peeled Russet potatoes that have been steamed, grated and seasoned with corn flour and salt before getting a tan in the oven for an hour. If you thought that’s the end, it’s certainly not as the potato is then fried and topped with sour cream and fresh za’atar. This might seem like any other hashbrowns that you can get elsewhere but #nothingistooimproper when it comes to Artichoke. The crispy outer shell is just the first layer of amazingness before you reach deeper in to get the warm and starchy potato. The sour cream gives it an uplifting zing that awakens your palate while the spices accentuate the flavour and aroma.
_________________
Artichoke Singapore
Address: 161, Middle Road, Singapore 188978
_________________

9-pound cannon, one of a pair originally used as decorations for the main gate of Fort Canning. <369> “Interesting Ways To Enjoy The Beach At High Tides” 

What do you do when the waves are almost swept up to the edge of the beach?

Surely, you cannot build sand castles. There wasn’t much sand to walk on the beach as the waves were breaking close. But I discovered some interesting ways to enjoy the beach at high tides —take a selfie at the high rocks with your loved ones, take a walk barefooted in the water, or take a dip behind the rocks!

William

post_caption: I was contacted by @originalnewdelhi to do up a short vlog-ish short video, and I’ve never actually done vloggy things before. But I tried it anyway and here I am. ALL KINDS OF FEEDBACK ARE WELCOME.

293/365
Takumar 50mm F1.4 and Sigma 35mm F1.4
.
I’ve been taking this online course by @jordhammond about travel photography. It cleared out questions I had about how to do travel photography. 
.
It’s been great experience, but most of the successful examples I see in his videos are way different from my current style and I’m not sure to what extent I should stick to “my style” and how much I should skew my style to more appealing look while keeping my personality.
I know my look isn’t appealing to majority of people, but I don’t want to sell my soul just to gain popularity...nor do I want to stay where I am and not be successful.
It’s a struggle. Hmmm 🤔 
.
.
.
.

Elephant creeper is often grown as trellis on fences, pergolas or simply inside a container.

[Little India Precinct] - The Flower Guys of Little India

This is dedicated to the friendly and 
handsome flower garland selling guys of Little India.

Rediscovery is about relooking and presenting the beauty of people in their environment

I am always attracted to the stalls selling colorful flower garlands. Those flower garlands are used for religious purposes during those festivals. Often, those guys are so friendly and always open for a nice photo and chitchat. As I rediscover, I see the beautiful people ( those eyes.. ) and color flower. Cannot help but to capture them in my photos.

*Taken during the stipulated period .Hope that this project to re-discover Singapore can spark the interest of Singaporean exploring more of Singapore.

294/365
Takumar 50mm F1.4 and Sigma 35mm F1.4
.
Thank you for giving me the permission to take photo of you, sir! He caught my eye as he was standing in the light in this dark Hawker center. I should’ve also asked what he was looking at outside. He seemed interested in something that’s happening there.
.
For a long time, I had been thinking no one would EVER let me take photography of them, but actually a lot of people are ok with it. My next goal is to get to know more about them after taking photo.
People are full of stories. I want to know more about how people are living here.
Singapore may be a small country and I thought I’ve been to everywhere, but you can never know all about it.
.
.
.

Today is the 15th day of the 8 month in the Chinese calendar. It is the day set aside for family reunions, but also the time when the moon is at its most bright.  The Mid Autumn Festival or Moon Festival will have people gather to sample autumn harvests. In our case, most people here enjoy mooncakes, consisting of many tasty flavors 😋 Usually it is a crazy travelling moment all across Asia but I guess this year is quite a special year eh?!

Happy Mid Autumn Festival to all our friends out there. What is the best tasting mooncake you have had? Have you had one before?

This pretty shop selling Arabic-style lights looks like a typical shop in Turkey but it is actually located in Kampong Glam right here in Singapore!

Kampong Glam is an eclectic blend of history, culture and a trendy lifestyle scene. Traditional stores selling textile and handicrafts, such as the one seen here, exist happily alongside hipster cafes and designer labels.

Do you know that #KampongGlam was once designated for the Malay royalty? 😏

A timely reminder to all in this COVID-19 Pandemic; Singapore's Ok! sculpture Park was built after Singapore successfully won the SARS outbreak in 2003. 

Each finger represent a message:
1) Eat healthy, exercise regularly 
2) Wash hand with soap frequently
3) Do not litter. Bag your rubbish and place in bin
4) See doctor, avoid crowded places if unwell. Spit, cough and sneeze into tissue
5) Keep public toilet clean. Keep places clean and free of pests.

The good old days at Tee Seng Store. Putting everything together, hope u like it...

Provision shop in a home. 80-year-old Mr Ang is the key figure at Tee Seng Store and has been working here since 1955. Waking up at 5am everyday to practise qigong before opening his shop at 8am as he wants to stay get healthy so that he can continue to work here with his beloved wife.

He knows his regular what they want even before they asked. One of his customer shared the store has the biggest and fresh eggs.
An empty Milkmaid tin that was used to store cash in the past. Mr Ang now uses a scanner cash register.

What impressed me most was Mr Ang had learnt many languages  like Thai, Java, Tagalog, Malay, Tamil and Sinhala. He shared knowing these languages helps give that personal touch to the customers. Of course there's one language he wished to pick up and thats Jap. 

I am fortunate that Mr Ang allows me to take a shot of him and chat with his childhood days and all his experience since young till now and of course this kampung spirit and experience is something supermarket chains can never give you...

The third #SingapoRediscovers series: Changi Jurassic Mile. This newest and largest permanent outdoor display of life-sized dinosaurs is part of the Changi Airport connector and the opening was recently officiated by the Minister of Transport on 11 Oct 2020.

With this connector, we now have the option to cycle, walk and jog to East Coast Park and Marina Bay from Changi Airport (in addition to other modes of transport like the bus, train or taxi).

While admission is free, do remember to refer to the website to verify if you are required to do any pre-booking prior to your visit. As the path is also shared among cyclists, runners and pedestrians, let us remain vigilant and be considerate to ensure that all users are safe when visiting this attraction!

And yes, keep your hands and bodies off the exhibits please.

post_caption:
“When the Circuit Breaker started, it was like a ghost town. It’s heartbreaking, especially for my mother, who is known to be a chatterbox.”

Tucked in the corner of Little India, @rasoolshop_sg has been selling special spice mixes blended from their family’s secret recipes for over 60 years — even before Singapore achieved independence! They are so popular that their customers come from all over the world, even famous ones (who can’t be named 😉).

But for the first time in all their years of operations, Shah and his mother — the folks behind Rasool Shop — found themselves stuck in a predicament. Business was poor, and customer footfall was low amid COVID-19.

Luckily, they managed to find new ways of reconnecting with old customers and new friends by bringing their shop online. Now, anyone can easily purchase Rasool’s spices with just one click!

Look out for Rasool’s story tomorrow at 6:30pm!

#GrowingThroughChallenges

There are dinosaurs in Singapore!! 🦖
But as you can see, don’t worry they won’t eat you if you get too close🙅🏻‍♂️
The new Jurassic Mile trail in Changi has nine different types of dinosaurs on display. They include a fierce T-rex trying to break out of its cage, a Brontosaurus dipping its long neck into a pond for a drink, and mischievous baby Pterodactyls stealing golf balls from the nearby course ⛳️🏌🏻‍♂️
Entry is free for all cyclists and joggers (or walkers, like me, haha). I for some reason thought it a good idea to walk from East Coast Park to the Jurassic Mile, and then onward to Jewel Changi. I can’t feel my legs now😂😂

Another spot at #ToaPayoh Central that has transformed over the years.

The spot where the local @courtssg outlet occupied used to be the post office which in front of it stood a sculpture of a man lifting a woman, although I am quite sure the post office was not the first occupant of the old building.

The two housing blocks at the back of the picture used to be two of four accommodated the athletes competing in the 1973 SEAP Games.

Lastly, the two-storey building on the right of the picture used to house the local outlet of the now-defunct Emporium (英保良) departmental store.

SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Kampong Lorong Buangkok

Kampong Lorong Buangkok, built in 1956, is probably the last Kampong in mainland Singapore

I decided to do a local tour there and I met with some very friendly folks, who are always obliging for a chat or phototaking

The kampong village retains the rustic beauty and it reminded me of my late uncle house's  in Pasir Ris Kampong

The kids here run freely and love it here. The 70 year old uncle I spoke to, says the family always like to gather at their mom's house on weekend

You can see herbs, mango, banana and even a coca tree here.

Along the way, we met some visitors who brought their kids to learn more about our traditional kampong heritage.

This is certainly an enjoyable  trip and would suggests everyone, to experience this kampong way of life. 

Just make sure you respect their privacy if they are not keen to have their pictures taken.

Note: Permissions have been granted to take the pictures of the residents, in their house compound, from afar.

Shooting the Masjid Sultan - or Sultan Mosque - and Bussorah Street as they should be experienced: a pair 🕌 #SeteMilKmEmSingapura ⠀
⠀
This neighbourhood has been here for 200 years and is Singapore's Arab Quarter, but the truth is you can find touches of soooo many cultures in Kampong Glam! The area offers a unique mix of Malay, Chinese, European, Indonesian and Islamic architecture, cuisine and art - I love how walking around Singapore feels like visiting several different countries at once ❤️⠀
⠀
⠀
🇧🇷 Foto da Masjid Sultan - ou Mesquita do Sultão - e da Rua Bussorah, que ficam ainda mais lindas juntas! 🕌 ⠀
⠀
Essa área é habitada há 200 anos e é conhecida como o bairro muçulmano de Singapura, mas a verdade é que você vai encontrar toques de muuuuitas culturas em Kampong Glam! O bairro tem uma mistura única de arquitetura, culinária e arte malaia, chinesa, européia, indonésia e muçulmana - AMO como os passeios em Singapura parecem uma viagem por vários países! ❤️⠀

Do you know you’ll get to try on this #fomepress table top printing press during the intro to linocut printing workshop? Many of our past participants love this Italian masterpiece for its easy-to-use and even print results! ⁣
⁣
Sign up for the workshop, link in bio. ☝🏻⁣
⁣
Date: Saturday, 17 October 2020⁣
Time: 14.00 - 17.00⁣
Instructor: Hairul Latiff⁣
Location: 727 North Bridge Road #02-01, Singapore 198695⁣
⁣
Course Fee: SGD35⁣
Price inclusive of tools and materials⁣
⁣
Join us to experience a printmaking session where you will be introduced to the basics of linocut carving and printing techniques. You will begin by tracing the selected pattern or design and transferring them onto the lino surface. Then, using various linocut blades, you will carve the lino block to create a positive image. Finally, you will ink the image using a brayer with block printing ink and print the image onto paper.⁣
⁣

Happy 1st Birthday, Jewel @ Changj Airport
.
Officially opened on October 18th, 2019. Jewel receives about 300,000 visitors a day. In October 2019, six months after its soft opening, it had already welcomed 50 million visitors, exceeding its initial target for the whole of the first year. 
In November 2019, Jewel Changi Airport was awarded the Special Jury Award at the year's Mapic Awards, which recognises excellence, innovation and creativity in the global retail real estate industry. Jewel Changi Airport had initially submitted entries in two categories - Best Leisure Concept and Best Shopping Mall - but the panel, comprising top retail real estate experts, gave it the Special Jury Award, which goes to the jury's favourite project among all the entries.

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct] Beyond the colorful

Rediscovery is about having a listening ear and appreciation to the heritage of the place.

Joo Chiat is a place with so much rich history as well as street “historians”. In both visits, I have had strangers who are residents or former residents coming to chit chat with me. They told me interesting stories as well as places to shoot. Most of us, including myself, will focus a lot of attention on the colorful peranakan house.  One of them ( her name is Diana)  was told that there are more. For example, I should also be paying attention to the tiles of those other chinese or penakan houses. Those are imported from Europe in the pre-war days, and often use a symbol of wealth for people staying in the area. 

She also shared something interesting about what is shown in the last photo. Can you guess what that is for?

post_caption:
A kampong's beauty
.
The Last Kampong in Singapore - Appreciate that the last kampong on Singapore’s mainland, not only does Lorong Buangkok serve as an important cultural and historical symbol, I feel that its camaraderie is also something that we can learn from. Residents there welcome each other’s presence and help each other out.
Even though HDB flats attempt to imitate the kampong spirit and induce cohesion among the residents, the camaraderie present is but only a feeble imitation of the kampong spirit.

Kampong Buangkok’s postal code was 1954, when Singapore still used only four digits for postal codes before 1st September 1995. It has since been changed to a six-digit postal code now, but this sign remains as a nostalgic reminder. There's always a sense of warmth and presence of human touch in such a peaceful environment like how friendly Mak Cik (malay auntie) was when I chatted with her. 
Hope this place will be kept and allow the younger generations to learn those valuable lessons we can never learn in class.

Remember to seek Mr and Miss Sng for approval to walk through this wonderful kampong. Seek the residents permission and respect the residents' privacy when are in their premises. 
.

There’s never a bad time to enjoy hotpot! And if you’re a fan of Beauty In The Pot (like us! 😋), chances are, you’ve probably eaten the seafood from this family’s business before. 

As self-professed seafood lovers, Hong Seafood supplies their frozen products to popular restaurant chains like Paradise Group and hotels from Shangri-La to Ritz Carlton. 

This humble family business started from only selling prawns, to now supplying a wide array of seafood to both local and international establishments. But when borders closed and dine-ins at local eateries stopped amid the COVID-19 outbreak, they found themselves facing their biggest challenge in 34 years of operations.

Hear how they managed to rise above the odds at 6:30pm tomorrow — on all of our platforms!

Family Outing
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

The Sembawang Hot Springs Park is a natural hot spring & a public park in Singapore. It is located beside a military camp about 100 metres (330 ft) off the main road, Gambas Avenue. Like hot springs worldwide, it can have health healing properties with proper use in moderation, & its natural spring water had once been bottled commercially by Fraser & Neave, under the brand name of Seletaris. Since its discovery in 1909, the spring has been through a few changes of ownership & potential redevelopment proposals. The hot spring has a rural rustic feel for visitors to unwind from the hustle & bustle of the modern metropolitan city. The National Parks Board took over the ownership of the park for redevelopment, which officially reopened on 4 January 2020. It's one of the two hot springs in Singapore with the other located on Pulau Tekong.

【Sengkang #1 – Char Siew Noodle】
Situated at the North-Eastern part of Singapore, Sengkang was once occupied by fishing villages, rubber and pepper plantations. During the mid-20th century, this area was known as “Kangkar” which literally means “Foot of Harbour”.

Although with younger generations residing at this district, the love of local hawker food remains identical to any other part of Singapore. Sengkang has a wide array of hawker fare and even had their very first vending machines café for all the dabao-food lovers.

To kick-start our feature on Sengkang, we picked a traditional staple menu in most hawker centres – Char Siew Noodle.
 
A perfect serving of Char Siew Noodle contains egg noodles cooked al dente, tossed in flavoured sauce and topped with slices of yummy, slightly charred roast pork and leafy vegetables. Simple but satisfying!

Where is your favourite Char Siew Noodle stall? Comment below to tell us where to find this traditional dish. Stay tuned for our post when we reveal the stall name and learn about our behind-the-scenes process. See ya.
