Delightful chaos and beautiful disarray. That is usually the state of the studio after a full day of workshops.
.
TBH, preparing for and cleaning up after classes take up a lot of time and frankly aren't much fun at all. And these are just some of many invisible behind-the-scenes things we do to create the art experience we want to deliver for every single guest who visit the studio. 
.
But the hard work all pays off when we see the galore of works that our workshop participants create after every session. Each piece different and always inspiring in one way or another. And if even when only one person leaves the studio having a renewed perspective towards art, we do a little dance in our heart.💃
.
So when you're feeling tired like we do today, take a moment to look for that delight in chaos and beauty in disarray, and then find new strength to keep going. For us, we wake up grateful every day to be able to call this our career, our passion and our mission 👩🏻‍🎨 Here's to another brand new day. Fighting!
.
#gratitude🙏 #artforthesoul #whywedowhatwedo

Meet the 🌈 multi-coloured old Hill Street Police Station! It is one of Singapore’s favourite spot for visitors and locals alike that love to take photos! This Skittles-like facade with 900+ windows is quite central and convenient to get to. It is at the Clarke Quay MRT station 🚉  and after your photo session here, you can either go hang around #ClarkeQuay for a drink or a munch... or head over towards Fort Canning, a beautiful oasis in the middle of the city, also home to a few other very photogenic places!

This structure dates back to 1934 and once housed the Hill Street Police Station and Barracks. Today, it is used by the Ministry of Communications and Information and Ministry of Culture, Community and Youth.

post_caption:
A different experience exploring in the dark and coming up close to animals at night. You can only do this at the Night Safari, the world's first nocturnal zoo! It was the kids' first time at the Night Safari and we had a great time there! There were moments where it was pitch dark when we were on the tram and our senses were heightened so we could spot, hear or smell something nearby. 

Swipe to check out our video where we had close encounters with hyenas and cheetahs! 

The kids were exhausted after we exited the Night Safari because it was close to their bedtime but they agreed that it was an awesome and refreshing experience to see animals at night. We missed the Creatures of the Night Show because it was full but we will be back again!

5 OCt 2020

Ang Mo Kio in Hokkien literally means the ‘red-haired man’s bridge’, where ang mo is a colloquial term for a Caucasian person. The name makes reference to the bridge over Kallang River in the area, built by Johnson Turnball Thomson, Government Surveyor of the Straits Settlement from 1841 to 1853. Another saying was that there were 9 bridges connecting the rural area back in those days, earning it the name ‘Kow Tiao Kio’ or Hokkien for ‘9 bridges’.

The town was largely uninhabited until the rubber boom in the beginning of the 20th century, which brought cultivation and habitation to the Chinese district. Ang Mo Kio comprised mainly farms and attap houses scattered among rubber estates.

Indonesia dan Singapura sedang sedang membahas Reciprocal Green Lane (RGL) dalam program Safe Travel Corridor.⁣
⁣

View from HDB City Vue @ Henderson

At City Vue @ Henderson, you will discover plenty of recreational options that cater to the residents of all ages. Children will enjoy playing at the children’s playgrounds. Fitness enthusiasts can stretch their muscles at the adult and elderly fitness stations, or engage in games at the hard courts. Those who wish to gather with the neighbours for a friendly chat can do so at the resting shelters and precinct pavilions. The roof garden above the multi-storey carpark will provide an ideal spot for quiet contemplation or an evening stroll.

Located at the junction of Tiong Bahru Road and Henderson Road, City Vue @ Henderson is sited close to Tiong Bahru MRT station and Tiong Bahru Plaza.

This development comprises 5 residential blocks ranging from 27, 40 and 48 storeys public housing flats. There are total of 1,232 units of 2-, 3-, 4- and 5-room Standard Flats.

The name City-Vue @ Henderson reflects its prime location close to the city.

.

Let’s talk about coffee.. ☕️⁣
To be honest, i never really like to drink coffee until my trip to New Zealand in 2017.. My husband bought a coffee and i took a sip, since then i am a convert! I was a tea lover but now i love coffee too! ⁣
⁣
The coffee i tried in New Zealand was The Flat White, then i also enjoyed having Latte.. And when i was on low carb diet i always had black coffee with butter or coconut oil.. It’s kinda weird but that combination boost my concentration and curb my hunger.. ⁣
⁣
I was stopped having caffeine when i got pregnant last year and now i am back enjoying coffee again.. My fav now is Latte.. What is your favourite coffee? ⁣
⁣

A  Busy  Street  Scene 

Chinatown Mid-Autumn Festival 2020.
@chinatown_festivals
Be enchanted by 700 sculptured lanterns along the streets of Chinatown. The lanterns display will depict traditional Chinese motifs and characters such as Chang’e, Goddess of the Moon in Chinese mythology, it will also illustrate this year’s theme – “family”, as a core element in getting Singaporean unite together as one big family to overcome the challenges ahead and emerge stronger.

Date: 17 September – 16 October 2020
Time: 7pm – 12mn (Daily)
Venue: Along New Bridge Road, Eu Tong Sen Street and South Bridge Road

HDB • 60 - 3 of 3

Ever since I was young i remember being fascinated at the different types of HDB estates out there (yes very nerd I know), the varying designs and amenities are never really the same for each area.

The #gobackhome photowalk series is for me personally a way to share with others my interest in HDB architecture, and I'm glad that this interest is being resonated with others as well.

Of course given that now COVID-19 has prevented us from gathering in large groups, photowalks have to be either postponed or scaled down.

It's been awhile since I have done one - perhaps it will be back sooner rather than later. #shapesofhome

Here are some food and product photos that I have shot and taught in my smartphone food photography workshops.

Recently, small grocers, chefs and home-based businesses approached me for product photography, mostly related to food and fresh produce.

With no photography budget, I said I will teach them instead, with a minimal fee, which is the simplest cost effective way to do it. 

Use your smartphone.

That is, if all you need is to upload to Instagram and Facebook. Smartphone images gives you the perfect resolution for that.

Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, almost all businesses especially small self owned ones are hard hit by loss of revenues.

Nevertheless, these business owners know that visuals are important for their business growth and social media marketing.

If you are one of them and want to learn how to create product images with no frills, drop me an email at info@carolinepang.com

I’m tall. Most of my photos are looking down on the subjects. This new camera position lets you see the world at the different level.

Bussiness goes on. . . Earning a living after the circuit breaker. The last of Singapore’s streetside barber start his busssiness during the phase one.

Undying dedication to his trade and a master of the art, the one old-school barber. Streetside barbers used to be a thriving industry back then. Haircuts, and shave has been his passion for the last 56 years. A "A+" classic... .
.
Mr Lee is located behind Moosehead along Telok Ayer Street and he usually opens from 10.30am-4pm from Mon-Fri and 10.30am-3pm on Sat. To make an appointment, call him at 97712146. I am so wanting to try nostril hair trim 😄

Waiting for phase 3 like… 🙄😬🥵🤞🏼

It’s been a while that I posted on here, as the situation in Singapore hasn’t changed yet. We have been in phase 2 of Singapore’s reopening for almost 4 months now and everybody seems to wait for updates on the situation. Meanwhile, I took the time to explore Singapore a little bit more and I always made sure I have my camera with me to capture the best food places and weekend getaways in our little red dot. So stay tuned for more local guides on my blog. Happy weekend and stay tuned! 💚

Es ist schon eine Weile her, dass ich hier gepostet habe. Die Situation in Singapur hat sich in den letzten Monaten nicht geändert, obwohl zumindest Corona im Griff zu sein scheint. Aktuell warten wir alle auf ein Update zu Phase 3, die hoffentlich ein paar Lockerungen mit sich bringt. In der Zwischenzeit hatten wir mehr als genug Gelegenheiten, auch die letzte Ecke Singapurs zu erkunden. Und wir finden immer wieder neue interessante Nachbarschaften, ausgezeichnete Restaurants und interessante Spots. Selbstverständlich habe ich immer meine Kamera dabei und schreibe gerade fleißig an neuen Beiträgen für meinen Blog. Ihr dürft also gespannt sein ☺️ Bis dahin wünsche ich euch allen ein schönes Wochenende. ✨

「05 Oct 2020」
Have a RAWRSOME Monday! 🦖
#littlehayashisushi
#momandson
#firstborn
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
We were at @rwsentosa USS last Friday. I was surprised that Sushi had so much fun and was so brave in trying out the rides! I thought we were gonna be on the carousel for 10 times to make our $66 worth it. However, he surprised me when he requested to take the roller coaster at Jurassic World (the legs dangling one). I checked many times as we were queuing to make sure he know what were taking because I was super scared. Guess what? He loved it and I was the one screaming my lungs out. He requested to go again, and refused to get off the 2nd round 😅#thingsmomwoulddoforkids 
He came home and told everyone that he took the rollercoaster and he protected mama because mama was screaming. Such a sweet darling! 
I am just glad to have spent some quality time with him, even if it meant messy hair, sweaty face, getting blisters on my feet, having heat rash and running around to catch the meet n greet despite my burning achilles, it is ALL WORTH IT to see how much he enjoyed himself. ❤️
If you are heading down, do remember to purchase the tickets with @mastercard to receive a complimentary halloween special mask and a gudetama notebook! Head down at 12pm to meet n greet the characters and trick n treat with the Candy Ambassadors and have early access to the rides!🎃👻 I must say that they did a good job with the crowd control and safe distancing within the compound, because the queue was a maximum of 30min wait and we didn’t see crowds anywhere. Thank you safe distancing ambassadors for keeping us safe while we play. #thankful
Most importantly, don’t forget to bring an extra set of clothes and MASK for both you and your kids! You don’t want to wear a sweat soak mask for 5hrs... #notsponsored #justsharing #thanksforreading #happymonday

【Sengkang #3 - Herbal Soup】
Well known for its calmness and tranquility, Sengkang Riverside Park offers an array of activities for nature lovers. Designed with a “fruity” theme, this wetland is about the size of a football field which helps to collect rainwater naturally through its aquatic plants. Wow!

As health foods go, herbal soup has been always been the favourite among many Singaporeans. Fragrant rice is cooked and served with a flavourful herbal chicken soup, believed to have benefits from detoxification to healing and strengthening the body. Each restaurant boasts its own closely-guarded secret herbal recipe of up to 20 different ingredients.

Make a trip to the nearest coffee shop and let us know where you get your healthy nutritious broth. A perfect pairing will be a glass of warm barley water! Burp!

Do you know of any hawkers that sell such herbal soup? Comment below to tell us where to find these delicious pastries. Stay tuned for our post when we reveal the stall name and learn about our behind-the-scenes process. See ya.

Changi Jurassic Mile 🦕🦖with permanent exhibits is officially opened on 11 Oct 2020 😃 
Between 16 Oct 2020 to 3 Jan 2021, visitors will have to reserve a slot on Changi PlayPass https://playpass.changiairport.com/ or iChangi App if planning to visit the Jurassic Mile on Fridays, Saturdays and Sundays between 9am and midnight due to current COVID-19 era safe distancing concerns.

Approx. 20 mins walk from Hub & Spoke cafe (next to Changi Airport Terminal 2 Carpark 2A end / across South Carpark) via the new Changi Airport Connector (red pathway) to reach Changi Jurassic Mile 🦖🦕 ;
or just take bus or vehicle directly to Changi Airport Terminal 4 Carpark 4A that is next to one of the entrance of Changi Jurassic Mile. We took about 1 hour 10 mins to walk to-and-fro the stretch of Changi Jurassic Mile 🦖🦕 including some time spent on photo-taking 📷📸

新加坡🇸🇬最新打卡景点：Changi Jurassic Mile 🦕🦖 @ Changi Airport Connector. Next to Changi Airport Terminal 4, Carpark 4A.
开放24小时、入场免费、永久展览；在疫情期间，如果打算在每逢星期五至星期天的时段参观，必须上 Changi Airport 的网站或 iChangi App 预定入场票。

I've passed by Bedok Reservoir Park numerous times on practically all sides, but this is the first time I've gone in! 😅

It's a lovely place to exercise and de-stress, and quiet on a weekday early afternoon when I was there. One could sit with a book at the many sheltered spots in the park.

The solar farm is a great idea, making use of what nature provides. There's construction work going on, so I expect there'll be more attractions like the flying fox adventure park and kayaking coming up. I hope it won't get too busy, but I suppose Singapore has to optimise all its limited resources.

Where are you going?!

Do you guys have a side you prefer to be on in pictures? Liz loves the left, so she’ll always sneak in either way to pose on the left. This is one of the few times we mix it up😂

This was at the iconic Raffles Hotel - the very first Raffles in sunny Singapore. Opened in 1887, it started as a beach house. Now it’s a symbol of unparalleled service, charm, and splendour in the most storied building on the island!

One day, when the world opens up again, and you find yourself in Singapore, you must stay at this legendary haven, even for a night, and savour a Singapore Sling🍹

Have you been to Kampong Lorong Buangkok before? 

Made up of 26 single-story wooden houses, the area is the only surviving traditional village in Singapore.

Grandlink Square, with the front facade of the former queen's theatre.

It used to be an entertainment place until it ceased its operation in 1982. Today, the current building is occupied by Grandlink square, retaining the front facade.  The facade now is under the conservation area of URA (Urban Redevelopment Authority).

Rediscovering Sg means to walk around the neighbourhood instead of taking public transport because who knows we might spot a hidden gem at the corner of the street, which led me to this historical place.

Beneath the ground lies the old gunpowder magazine, a storehouse for gunpowder. When the artillery was removed from Fort Canning, it was converted into a shooting range for target practice. The area was also previously used as living quarters for married officers and their families, with a military hospital nearby. #rediscoversg #singaporediscovers #whatmakessg #mysingapore

7-8 years ago (I think), I came here alone and explored this north part of #singapore with a deep history of #colonial past. Things have remained pretty much the same - there has been no upgrade or redevelopment to this area in #seletar which used to house British military staff. Nonetheless,  the bungalows are one of a kind with double chimneys and even with maid chambers. They are probably beautiful and glorious in the olden days, and though old and derelict and abandoned now, they look as beautiful amidst nature looking to take over the houses. Given their long abandoned state, there is also something eerie about the windows, I can imagine pairs of eyes looking out! Hahaha . I wouldn't dare to explore the insides of the houses, despite my curiosity.  Some of the houses (those with glass panels and are refurbished) are now for commercial use. Within the surroundings, there are also many interesting streets with #british #streetnames such as Hyde Park (the last time I visited, it was barricaded for redevelopment) and Oxford Street, a huge reminder of our colonial past. For now, I can also make pretend that I am travelling in the UK 😁🤣 oh ya, check out the super unique tree in the first picture! Have never seen anything quite like it!

Good news! Many hotels are reopening, just in time for an end-of-year getaway 😍 Here are some unique staycation ideas that will make you forget that you are actually in Singapore.⁣
⁣
The Warehouse Hotel is known for its historic industrial character, transporting us back in time to experience the old-world glamour.⁣
⁣
Next, we have So Sofitel, housed in a neo-classical heritage building in the heart of the city. The hotel is a perfect blend of French elegance and local cultures, recommended for couples looking for a romantic stay! ⁣
⁣
Last but not least, if you are into nature and minimalistic interiors, be sure to check out Lloyd's Inn for a tranquil and immersive experience. It is located in Somerset, just a five-minute walk away from the Orchard Road shopping belt!⁣
⁣
Which fits your vibe best?⁣
⁣
1. 📷 @thewarehousehotel⁣
2. 📷 @sosofitelsingapore⁣
3. 📷 @lloydsinn⁣

post_caption:
Changi Jurassic Mile 🦕🦖with permanent exhibits is officially opened on 11 Oct 2020 😃 
Between 16 Oct 2020 to 3 Jan 2021, visitors will have to reserve a slot on Changi PlayPass https://playpass.changiairport.com/ or iChangi App if planning to visit the Jurassic Mile on Fridays, Saturdays and Sundays between 9am and midnight due to current COVID-19 era safe distancing concerns.

Approx. 20 mins walk from Hub & Spoke cafe (next to Changi Airport Terminal 2 Carpark 2A end / across South Carpark) via the new Changi Airport Connector (red pathway) to reach Changi Jurassic Mile 🦖🦕 ;
or just take bus or vehicle directly to Changi Airport Terminal 4 Carpark 4A that is next to one of the entrance of Changi Jurassic Mile. We took about 1 hour 10 mins to walk to-and-fro the stretch of Changi Jurassic Mile 🦖🦕 including some time spent on photo-taking 📷📸

新加坡🇸🇬最新打卡景点：Changi Jurassic Mile 🦕🦖 @ Changi Airport Connector. Next to Changi Airport Terminal 4, Carpark 4A.

Arranged in nine chapters about our take on #Covid19, it showcases 140 works by 91 Singapore based creatives who consist of photographers, videographers, writers, artists, architects and designers.

These are the images I captured during and after the “Circuit Breaker”. Most of the photos are primarily blue in colour, reflecting the blue mood: lots of uncertainty and a feeling of loneliness.

Blue, however, is also the colour of the sea and sky, which I was able to spend more time admiring and learning to appreciate nature more.

Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

The Sembawang Hot Springs Park is a natural hot spring & a public park in Singapore. It is located beside a military camp about 100 metres (330 ft) off the main road, Gambas Avenue. Like hot springs worldwide, it can have health healing properties with proper use in moderation, & its natural spring water had once been bottled commercially by Fraser & Neave, under the brand name of Seletaris. Since its discovery in 1909, the spring has been through a few changes of ownership & potential redevelopment proposals. The hot spring has a rural rustic feel for visitors to unwind from the hustle & bustle of the modern metropolitan city. The National Parks Board took over the ownership of the park for redevelopment, which officially reopened on 4 January 2020. It's one of the two hot springs in Singapore with the other located on Pulau Tekong.

post_caption:
[Under-the-radar hub-and-spoke café ✈️☕️]

@hubandspokecafe is a very young new ground level café located just minutes away from @changiairport Terminal 2. 

Most of the café's offerings are western-style brunch, pastas, salads, breakfast toasts, and the usual coffee/tea offerings. What stands out and to keep with modern times, is that they have bubble tea offerings too. 

This isn't a food review though, but just to publicise such a place exists. 

Also, they accept your own cups and bottles if you wish to use your own to-go cup in replacement of the single-use cups they offer for cold drinks! 💚 

The café also has showers (coming soon)! 🚿🛀

Right now, the café has great views of the main road, which includes glimpses of buses passing by as they exit the Terminal 2 Passenger Building. 🚌🚌

One incentive to visit this café is if you cycle along the Park Connector Network from East Coast Park via the Jurassic Mile. Bicycle racks are available, with a bicycle rental service by Go Cycling as well. 🚲

There is a vending machine selling items from cables to wet tissues and face masks.

If you are going to take a walk from @jewelchangiairport , it's about 2k–3k+ steps each way via the Terminal 2–Jewel link bridge. 

Once any travel bubble or when the SQ tours set in, hopefully we will see more traffic at this cornerside café. It's not that accessible unless you park at the South Carpark near Terminal 2 or the Carpark 2A and walk in (if it's open?).
.
.
2020
Changi Airport, Singapore

post_caption:
HDB Central Horizon

At HDB, the development of Selective En bloc Redevelopment Scheme (SERS) replacement projects to high standards of quality, design, and environmental innovation. As a result, many SERS replacement projects have won prestigious awards and accolades. These is just one of the examples.

The Development:

Block 79 Toa Payoh Central used to be a single 10-storey block. Today, the site is home to Central Horizon, a distinctive Toa Payoh landmark offering scenic panoramas of central Singapore.

HDB Central Horizon is made up of 5 towering 40-storey blocks, with a total of 1,158 units of 4-and 5-room flats.

The Honours:

• HDB Design Excellence Award 2008 (Housing Category)

• BCA Universal Design Award for Build Environment 2009 (Residential Building Category)

• SIA-NParks Skyrise Greenery Award 2009

[Sembawang Precinct] The most beautiful neo-classic seafacing  and romantic heritage building 

Rediscovery is about capturing something beautiful in a new perspective. 
Beaulieu House may be one of Singapore's most well-preserved neo-classica and romanticl heritage buildings facing straits of Johor. The name means beautiful place in French and was built in 1910 by Jewish Businessman  Joseph Brook David as a holiday home.

I have decided to present this building in a different perspective to showcase its beauty as I re-visited the place recently. Great to visit with your lover ones.

✨ [Pulau Ubin Guided Tour from $58/person] ✨
.
Take a day trip to this beautiful island and discover all the beauty that it has to offer. Visitors will be picked up from their homes 🏠 to the jetty and take a 15-min bumboat ride 🛶 to the island with our licensed tourist guide.
.
You will have a glimpse into Singapore's yesteryears, alongside 🌴 coconut rubber plantations, fish farms and Singapore’s last-remaining kampong (traditional village).
.
Originally known as Pulau Batu Jubin (Granite Stone Island in Malay), this 1020-hectare island’s granite quarries once provided the stone used to construct structures like the Istana and the Singapore-Johore Causeway.

 ⁣

 ⁣
Join us to experience a printmaking session where you will be introduced to the basics of linocut carving and printing techniques. You will begin by tracing the selected pattern or design and transferring them onto the lino surface. Then, using various linocut blades, you will carve the lino block to create a positive image. Finally, you will ink the image using a brayer with block printing ink and print the image onto paper.⁣

Hydrotherapy
Natural Spring Water
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

According to local geologists, the exact source of the spring remains unknown, but it is believed that its origin may be southwest of its actual location, possibly at Bukit Timah. Hot springs are formed when underground water comes into contact with hot rock masses. The resulting high pressure causes the water to seep upwards through cracks, forcing itself out of the ground as a spring.

A series of tests conducted by the PSB Corporation and SGS Testing & Control Services found the spring water contains 420 mg of chloride per litre, an amount which is substantially higher than the 35 to 100 mg in the water from Choa Chu Kang & Bedok waterworks. It was also found that the sulphide content is three times more than tap water & the spring water is also slightly alkaline due to the presence of minerals. Natural spring waters may have health benefits, similar to the hot springs of other countries near tectonic plates with volcanoes, in a search for cures for some skin conditions, as well as debilitating ailments like rheumatism & arthritis. Although local rheumatologists conceded that hydrotherapy is an accepted treatment that can be helpful for mild forms of rheumatism or muscle strain, they, along with dermatologists, remain skeptical of claims about the alternative healing of the natural spring water.

Hot hard water bubbles continuously in the well, releasing a slightly unpleasant sulphur mud-like odour together with steam. The temperature of the spring water is measured by precision instrument to be constant 70 °C (160 °F). In an investigation carried out by the Nanyang Technological University in 1994, the hot spring was found to have an estimated yield of approximately 150 litres (33 imp gal; 40 US gal) per minute at ground level through installed steel casings.

Double Rainbow over The Pinnacle @ Duxton HDB. What a beautiful view of the city from my neighbourhood at HDB Kim Tian Green. In this neighbourhood, there are seven blocks of 40 storey tall HDB public housing flats. Every flats have different breathtaking view of the city, ports, towns and nearby islands too. Sometimes, we may get to see rainbow in the morning or in the late afternoon just after the rain. Whenever I saw one in the sky, I will inform my neighbours so that they will not miss seeing the beautiful colours of the rainbow. And I quickly grab my camera and tripod, take the lift up to the highest floor to capture this amazing double rainbows over the city.

HDB Kim Tian Green:

Kim Tian Green have Blk 126A, 126B, 126C, 127A, 127B, 127C & 127D at Kim Tian Road are 40 storey HDB public housing flats in Bukit Merah, District 03, Singapore. It has a total of 214 units with 78 units of 3-room unit type and 136 units of 4-room unit type in every block. These flats were completed in 2011 and has a 90 years lease remaining. Kim Tian Green, Blk 126c, Kim Tian Road is located near Tiong Bahru Mrt Station (Ew17).

The initial destination was Kallang Riverside Park via PCN where available. It was a mistake! 😅 There were large sections where it was not continuous, and not only did I get lost and had to check with Google, I had to carry my bike up the overhead bridges which spanned the expressways! 💦 The sub 10kg bike made a HUGE difference! Once we got there, it seemed logical to carry on a little further to Marina Bay. 

It was very breezy and quiet at Kallang as well as Marina Bay and Merlion. It was obvious though from the very large bags of trash beside several bins that it was crowded earlier. It's a shame people can't pick up after themselves, or better yet, avoid disposables 😭

Decided to take the roads back, and made it back in half an hour, manual estimate 24 km/h average. A little bonus from Strava, I made it into the top 5 for 1 segment! 🤣 All because I wanted to get home to walk my dog and wasn't stopped by traffic lights!

As usual, Nerio and I were decked up like Xmas trees🌲
(Pics 4-6 on Samsung S20+ Pro mode, #Snapseed edit)

When my Mom came from overseas exploring Singapore, i brought her to visit landmarks such as Esplanade and Merlion Park.. ⁣
⁣
I told the taxi uncle to send us to Esplanade, but he didn’t seem to understand then we described it as “building with thorns” then he said “oh the Durian! OK! Let’s go!”⁣
Lol, so locals have dubbed it "the Durian", as the venue’s twin structures resemble the spiky tropical fruit.⁣
⁣
Durian is famous fruit here in Singapore.. Talking about this seasonal fruit, i hated it back then due to its pungent smell, however just few months ago during the season, my hubby brought home some durian and i can eat it! Since i become a mother, i feel that somehow i could accept and not too fussy on certain things lately.. ⁣
⁣
Anyway, “the Durian” always remind me of my mom, due to Covid, i am not so sure when i could see her again.. 😭⁣
.. ⁣

Singapore is known for her diversity in cultures, ethnicities and religions. Due to the travel restrictions and the SingapoRediscover campaign, I have started to explore our neighbourhoods and the history behind these places.

Most locals would know about the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple in Chinatown. This Tang-styled temple is an architectural icon and I like how it contrasts against the modern city skyline in the background. 

Did you know that the street beside it has a sombre history and is known as the "Dead People Street"? Early Chinese immigrants, many of whom had no relatives, lived out their last days in the death houses here. 

Today, this area is a lively and vibrant place. Chinatown Complex is built over part of the street and many elderly folks can be seen playing chess or checkers at the communal spaces. 

Do you know about the history of your neighbourhood? How about taking this opportunity to Rediscover Singapore?

Block 34 at Whampoa West is Singapore’s longest HDB block in the kallang district. It’s lengthy common corridors run along all 12 floors of the block, but what’s unique about the block’s design is its curved structure. The corridor is approximately 320 metres long and consists of 46 units per floor.

Fin de este par de días de "desconexión", o al menos de que me hagan la cama 🤣 Al estar en Singapur ahora mismo,no se puede salir fuera del país si quieres volver a entrar fácilmente, así que llevamos desde que nos mudamos sin salir de un país que de punta a punta tardas menos de una hora. En un principio teníamos reserva en el Marina Bay Sands,pero el viernes nos dijeron que ya no había slots para IR a la piscina( con todo esto del covid sólo se puede acceder por horarios y sólo una hora al día) Mal por su parte a la hora de hacer la reserva no indicar este pequeño detalle..😑 Total,no íbamos a pagar ir allí para no poder acceder a la piscina uno de los dos días y encima el segundo día sólo había hora a las 11 de la noche, así que cancelamos. Pero justo el viernes el Fullerton lanzó una oferta de 2x1(mucho más bonito que el Sands y también más caro de normal ), así que en el último momento reservamos y allí nos fuimos el domingo 😁

The afternoon tea ritual, a highly civilised affair conducted in oases of calm, has seen its fanbase swell over the last century or so and hotels are increasingly upping the ante to bring tea-time lovers through the door. Whether it’s sparkling teas, an afternoon experience that exudes geographical charm or even afternoon tea sets that you can buy and replicate the experience at home, we have evolved and come a long way from scones and clotted cream. Went to @gardensbythebay a few weeks ago before my injury. It was my first time visiting the Cloud Forest. I also brought along the @samsung_sg Galaxy Tab S7 to do some sketching at the Cloud Forest and also try out the Samsung tablet that I got.
.
The battery life is pretty good, it lasted the entire day and the pen can be used for drawing without charging. The sensitivity is on-point too. I used Clip Studio and Adobe Sketch for the sketches during my visit.
.
The cloud forest visit itself was a nice experience as well. I think I spent about two hours in it, the mosses reminded me of the trip to Kibune earlier this year.
.

Stroll through the colourful enclaves of Joo Chiat/Katong, home to hipster cafés, historical shophouses and Peranakan culture.  Immerse into the beautiful culture,  blend of old and new. Family businesses and quaint shophouses sit alongside cool cafés and hip boutiques.

Alongside the walls, the beautifully painted mural art will wow you and selfie worthy. 

Most of the murals here are a result of the Katong Joo Chiat Art Circuit ( #KJCArtCircuit ) organised by The Admin SG – same folk who set up Gelam Gallery in the back alleys of Kampong Glam – and commissioned by the Singapore Tourism Board to revitalise this area.
.

Culture and Fashion

It's difficult to not notice women dressed in Kurtis -- the most widely worn women traditional attire in India -- while strolling in Little India. As seen here, they come bright in colours and with floral designs. It brings out elegance and is stylish even in today's times. It's a no wonder that even young Indian ladies would wear them out on the streets today.

1. Elderly lady and her companion outside Tekka Centre.
2. Two ladies exiting from a shophouse onto Campbell Lane.
3. A lady waving for a taxi along Serangoon Road adjacent to Buffalo Road.

Appreciating the hidden gems of Little India, Joo Chiat and Chinatown 

📍Little India
•Little India - Once a place for racecourse, cattle herders and brick kilns. Now one of Singapore’s most vibrant districts.
•Little India Street Art / Five Foot Way -Explore Little India's rich multicultural history through its vibrant walls. ☝🏽On a side note, did you notice that 5-foot-way? the roofed continuous walkway commonly found in front of shops, the name refers to the width of the passageway. These walkways were meant to protect pedestrians from the hot tropical sun as well as rain.
•Deepavali Street Light Up - One of the major cultural festivals in Singapore, Deepavali (also known as “Diwali” or the “Festival of Lights”) is a celebration that marks the triumph of good over evil. 
•House of Tan Teng Niah - windows of the unique and colorful Chinese Villa that was built in 1900

📍Kampong Gelam
•Streetside Barbershop
•Spiral Staircases of Bugis - These external pre-cast concrete staircases first made their appearance at the rear of shophouses from the mid-1920s. Their introduction facilitated an important regular routine for households and residents living in the shophouses – the collection of night-soil. Night-soil is a euphemism for human faeces. The term came about, as human waste was collected in buckets in the silence of the night and sometimes, soil was used as a cover. A night-soil carrier would enter the alleys behind the shophouses and climb these spiral staircases to each storey. That was where buckets filled with night-soil were placed.

📍Joo Chiat
•Peranakan Shophouses of Joo Chiat

📍Chinatown
•Peranakan Shophouses of Bukit Paso 

In my heart, Singapore is more than just a face of industrialization. Inside her is a soft spot waiting to be discovered. She is more than just a pretty face. Indeed, worthy of our love and respect. Majulah Singupara!
.
📱on iPhone

SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Katong / Joo Chiat precinct

In Katong Joo Chiat area, you can discover conserved heritage shophouses with Peranakan culture or influence /designs.

Although this area is very well known for it's colourful street, Koon Seng Road, Katong Joo Chiat precinct, has other good attractions as well.

1. Teong Theng Co is a old school crafted rattan based furniture maker that has 70 years of history in Joo Chiat.  This is a good time to rediscover, some of our heritage shops and at the same time, feels the nostalgic vibes

2. China Collection (antique) shop is painted blue and white and this Chinese shop house  has now turn itself into a modern building with a minimal twist. Those who likes minimal design will appreciate the paint work

3. I couldnt resist taking a shot of this old school hair salon, everytime I pass by

4. Rumah Bebe in Katong is a Peranakan heritage boutique, a school, a bake shop and also a mini museum. I simply love the interior (more like exterior) decor.

-Vintage-

Taking a solo trip down to Little India alone last weekend to rediscover Singapore made me realise all the little things I overlook in life.

I had less pressure with time when I roamed around alone, and had the tenacity to speak to the people in the neighborhood. I learnt so much more when I spoke to the locals - Knowing why they came here for, what their struggles were (especially during this pandemic), their dreams and even the history of the places around us. And I truly miss traveling (solo) for the same reasons!

I don’t usually post carousels, but these pictures truly piece together a beautiful set of stories of what Little India is all about - A mix of old and new, people, culture, art and history.

1. A box of vintage old films outside Sajeev Digital Studio

2. The studio upstairs, where foreign workers take portraits to send home the pictures for their families to matchmake them with potential wives

3. Sajeev Digital Studio from outside

4. An Indian foreign lady, named Mary, who works outside a pop-up stall at House of Tan Teng Niah (the colorful house 2 posts before). She’s making prayer garlands using Jasmine, Rose, Orchid and Marigold and has been here for over 10 years

5. Massive mural which juxtaposes modern vehicles and the old-school way of transporting tiffins. Lorry as scale

6. Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple, Singapore’s oldest hindu temple that is dedicated to the goddess and destroyer of evil, Sri Veeramakaliamman or Kali. Early Migrant workers worship this goddess for safety in this new foreign land

This is the longest caption I have ever had, made with time, sweat, with sore legs and neck. Would appreciate it if you drop a comment below and tell me which photo caught your attention the most. Keep exploring, everyone!

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct] - Traditional Popiah

Rediscovery is about walking and finding unique place.  

As I rediscovered Joo Chiat, I came across Kway Guan Huat Joo Chiat - a traditional  Popiah maker since 1938 I was intrigued by the skill of those making the traditional popiah skin from dough. Great to see Chinese Fujian food culture still active and alive for over 80 years. It is also interesting to note that it coexisted for so many years next to the Malay enclave ( Geylang Serai) - Another reminder of our unique racial harmonious culture of Singapore.

<367> “Each Has Its Own Story To Tell”

Most trees look alike, but that’s not true. Look at each of them carefully! Don’t you see that every tree has its own story to tell? 

The same goes for people. Many people seem to lead similar lives, but the truth is that everyone is writing a different life story.

William

The Nine Emperor Gods Festival  is one of the most important religious events for the Taoist community in South East Asia. 
 
On the first day of the festival, the devotees gather along the shores of East Coast Park to wait for the arrival of the palanquins and the temple entourage from Leong Nam Temple –for the commencement of the receiving ceremony (“请水仪式 qing shui yi shi” in Mandarin). 
 
The ceremony is initiated by a priest who calls upon the Nine Emperor Gods to bestow his presence while devotees pray fervently with a joss stick in their hands.  After the initiation and invitation ceremony, the palanquins carrying the holy artefact (usually an urn) containing the Nine Emperor Gods continue to sway vigorously while the carriers attempt to depart from the coast, and back to the temple. 

Note: Adapted from www.heritagefestival.gov.sg

Stones Stacking
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

In 1998, the Ministry of Defence (Mindef) acquired the land containing the spring for the expansion of the nearby Sembawang Air Base, leaving F&N with less than 4 hectares (10 acres) of land. Its water-bottling plant survived until the early 1990s however. In January 2002, locals' interest to the hot spring, which had caught the attention of Singaporeans after the surrounding land had been cleared to begin the RSAF air base extension. Sembawang community leaders gathered signatures to petition Mindef, which was going to fence off the area, to preserve & develop the hot spring for the general public. Mindef gave the green light to the appeals & opened a small side gate pavement for the public to access the spring.

During that same year, a series of scalding cases, including an incident in which a senior citizen diabetic lost six toes to gangrene after soaking in the hot spring, prompted the Singapore General Hospital to warn that people with nerve disorders or diseases affecting blood circulation should be cautious to hot mineral springs. As a result of some negative rumors and hearsay, and the RSAF redevelopment, public interest began to wane & the number of visitors dwindled.

Takumar 50mm F1.4
Sony a7RIII
Today, I didn’t feel like I was getting “the shot.” When I am in that mental state, I start blaming the weather conditions, locations, lack of interesting subjects, etc. And everything I shoot start to look like they are bad. But @sixstreetunder said in his Skillshare class that you have to know that “the moment” may not come that day. Maybe something that you expected may not happen. You need to always adjust yourself to the changing moment. It’s what street photography is about. 
So, I decided to read an art book of Monet’s paintings to broaden my perspective. It said “Don’t see objects before you such as houses, clouds, statues, as what they are but see them as geometric shapes with colors.” The perspective made sense when I went outside. I was just thinking too much about the subjects. I’ll let go of the stress and just try to enjoy the moment.

Old & New
Toa Payoh Lorong 6 Dragon Playground
(Singapore Heritage)

The dragon-shaped sand-based playground used to be a popular design for playgrounds in Ang Mo Kio and Toa Payoh.

After 1993, they were phased out due to safety concerns and it is believed that this Dragon Playground of Toa Payoh (located at Blk 28 Toa Payoh Lorong 6) is the only one of its kinds (sand-based) left in Singapore (The other two are laid with rubber mats).

The dragon playground was designed in 1979 by Housing and  Development Board’s (HDB) in-house designer Khor Ean Ghee (born 1935), who got his inspiration from the Oriental dragon commonly seen among the Chinese community in Singapore.

Beside the majestic dragon, there are two little plastic rides in the shapes of a seahorse and a pony for children to sit on.

The long body of the dragon is made of steel rails which form a passage for kids to get to the dragon head. Using the slide, kids can descend from the dragon head to the sandy ground.

The Toa Payoh dragon playground was picked by New York culture blog, Flavorwire.com, in 2013 as one of 15 amazing playgrounds from all over the world.

HDB Toa Payoh Apex (Background):

HDB Toa Payoh Apex is bounded by Lorong 6 Toa Payoh and Toa Payoh East, approximately 10 minutes (1.1km) walk away from Toa Payoh MRT Station. 

This development consist of 557 units of 3- and 4-room Standard Flats. All 4 blocks of flats come with three-quarter height windows in the living/ dining area and half-height windows in other rooms. Highest floor is 36 storey.

Fusion food holds a special place in our heart (and stomach), living in a multicultural city like Singapore. Here are some of our favourite contemporary fusion restaurants you might not have heard of!⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Whitegrass is a fine dining restaurant showcasing classic French fare with a contemporary Japanese twist. Whitegrass focuses on using the freshest seasonal produce to create dishes that are thoughtful and respectful of nature. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Next, we have Restaurant Lerouy by the renowned Chef Christophe Lerouy. Tucked away on Stanley Street, Restaurant Lerouy offers a skilful blend of modern French cuisine with Asian ingredients. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
The list wouldn’t be complete without Wild Rocket, with their signature Mod-Sin cuisine. This cooking style takes on a modern and innovative approach toward local dishes. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣

Fort Gate, entrance to the British fort completed in 1860. Fort Canning was named after then-Governor-General of India, Lord Charles John Canning. It was built to protect Singapore from seaborne attacks. Fort Gate, the main entrance, faced the beach. A second purpose of the Fort was to be a refuge for the European population in the event of local unrest. #rediscoversg #singaporediscovers #whatmakessg #mysingapore

Nature is not a place to visit. It is home. —Gary Snyder

Grasses and weeds have a role in the ecosystem. There are many that are pretty too! 💚

Hydrocotyle verticillata, also known as whorled pennywort, whorled marshpennywort or shield pennywort, is a flowering plant found in South and North America and the West Indies. The creeping plants with unusual leaves give it its common names. It grows in places that are marshy, boggy, and wet. Hydrocotyle verticillata is used in aquaria, where it is undemanding but prefers a good substrate, and at least moderate light. It benefits from additional carbon dioxide.(Nature's #aircleaner!) (Source: Wikipedia)

Don't forget that you can also have a mental vacation, because those are just as important as the physical ones!

Some things can drain your energy and you definitely need to unplug!
The next time you feel anxious, ask yourself this: Does this deserve my energy? If it is a no, take a deep breath, disconnect, and come back IN FORCE!

And anyways, we can't really go on a physical vacation, so we went to Sentosa Island, formerly used as a British military base and then a Japanese prisoner-of-war camp in Singapore. Home of many theme parks, resorts, fun attractions and beach clubs, a stop here is a must whether you are a visitor or a local! #SingapoRediscovers

One of our top FAQ - What's your suggested itinerary? *How to island-hop all FOUR islands in a day!? 
. 
.
. 
1. Marina South Pier to St. John's Island (9.00am), then take the shuttle ferry from St. John's to Sisters' Island (10.00am)
2. Sisters' Island to Kusu Island (11.20am)
3. Kusu Island to St. John's Island (1.00pm/2.30pm)
4. Explore St. John's Island, 15-20min walk to Lazarus Island
5. St. John's Island back to Marina South Pier (4.00pm/6.00pm)
.
*Note: Our shuttle ferry is available on weekends/ph schedule only

Have you managed to shoot those stunning night scenes, light trails, smooth silky waters and more?

Check out my night photography workshop on Link in Bio. 

I’ll coach you the basic elements of night photography, providing you with tips and techniques of low light and long exposure photography. 

We will be working on camera settings to create different effects to capture fascinating images as the day changes from twilight hour into the night. 

No filter required!

Just practical stuff from your in-camera settings.

This workshop takes place at one of Singapore's most vibrant quays along the Singapore River, within a vicinity that is surrounded by historical and modern architecture. 

The location provides you with all the required subjects of interest to photograph in low light and to acquire the skills of night photography.

Book your spot through info@carolinepang.com

Nine Emperor Gods Festival 2020
龍南殿九皇大二帝爷千秋
九月初🗓🙏🙏🙏

The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia.

Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. 

This year the festival has scaled down considerably due to the Covid pandemic. Devotees, however, are still welcome to pray to the dieties but have to observe the social distancing measures in the temples.

The #avantgarde outlook of #Bishan #Library should grab the attention of anyone who stepped out from the nearly Junction 8 mall or from the bus interchange.

To cope with the demand because of the high usage in the nearby #ToaPayoh and Ang Mo Kio libraries, the establishment of this branch is a necessity and has been a popular spot for folks from all walks of life.

Besides a cafe that is incorporated on the ground level, there is also a book exchange corner outside the building where literacy gems can be founded among those placed in the book shelves.

Puddle Reflection
HDB Central Horizon

At HDB, the development of Selective En bloc Redevelopment Scheme (SERS) replacement projects to high standards of quality, design, and environmental innovation. As a result, many SERS replacement projects have won prestigious awards and accolades. These is just one of the examples.

The Development:

Block 79 Toa Payoh Central used to be a single 10-storey block. Today, the site is home to Central Horizon, a distinctive Toa Payoh landmark offering scenic panoramas of central Singapore.

HDB Central Horizon is made up of 5 towering 40-storey blocks, with a total of 1,158 units of 4-and 5-room flats.

The Honours:

• HDB Design Excellence Award 2008 (Housing Category)

• BCA Universal Design Award for Build Environment 2009 (Residential Building Category)

• SIA-NParks Skyrise Greenery Award 2009

post_caption:
Provision shop in a home. 80-year-old Mr Ang is the key figure at Tee Seng Store and has been working here since 1955. Waking up at 5am everyday to practise qigong before opening his shop at 8am as he wants to stay get healthy so that he can continue to work here with his beloved wife.

He knows his regular what they want even before they asked. One of his customer shared the store has the biggest and fresh eggs.
An empty Milkmaid tin that was used to store cash in the past. Mr Ang now uses a scanner cash register.

What impressed me most was Mr Ang had learnt many languages  like Thai, Java, Tagalog, Malay, Tamil and Sinhala. He shared knowing these languages helps give that personal touch to the customers. Of course there's one language he wished to pick up and thats Jap. 

I am fortunate that Mr Ang allows me to take a shot of him and chat with his childhood days and all his experience since young till now and of course this kampung spirit and experience is something supermarket chains can never give you...
.

.

.

SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Sembawang Hot Spring Park

The entrance of Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Sembawang Hot Spring Park is located in SingaporeSembawang Hot Spring Park
Type	Hot spring
Location	Sembawang, Singapore
Nearest town	Yishun
Coordinates	1.4344°N 103.8224°ECoordinates: 1.4344°N 103.8224°E
Area	1.1 hectares (11,000 m2)
Opened	4 January 2020; 8 months ago
Owned by	NParks
Public transit access	 NS13  Yishun
Facilities	Hot spring
Website	Official website
The Sembawang Hot Springs Park is a natural hot spring and a public park in Singapore.
It is located beside a military camp about 100 metres (330 ft) off the main road, Gambas Avenue. Like hot springs worldwide, it can have health healing properties with proper use in moderation, and its natural spring water had once been bottled commercially by Fraser and Neave, under the brand name of Seletaris. Since its discovery in 1909, the spring has been through a few changes of ownership and potential redevelopment proposals. The hot spring has a rural rustic feel for visitors to unwind from the hustle and bustle of the modern metropolitan city. The National Parks Board took over the ownership of the park for redevelopment, which officially reopened on 4 January 2020.
It's one of the two hot springs in Singapore with the other located on Pulau Tekong.

Old is indeed gold and time truly stood still here at Tong Ah Eating House the moment you stepped into the restaurant with all the interior setup and food that they are serving, which hasn’t changed much from many years ago. Instead of going for their extra crispy toast, we decided to get their French toast that comes with a slab of melting butter on top the toast with their own homemade moreish kaya by the side. The kaya is slightly different from the rest as theirs are eggier with a clumpy texture that is not as smooth as others. While the setup might not appeal to many, the quality of the traditional brewed Nanyang coffee more than makes up for it, the aroma and thickness will awaken any senses. I truly hope that the charm of this old-world heritage establishment remains as it is for many years to come to contrast all the modernization that is happening now to the F&B industry.
••••••••••••••••••••

Spring Well
“Village of Hot Water”
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

In 1909, a Chinese merchant named Seah Eng Keong, the son of Chinese pioneer Seah Liang Seah, discovered hot springs in his pineapple estate in Sembawang. The three springs were channelled into one, so that the water would be conveniently concentrated in one area. A well was built along with the spring, which became popular with the villagers, who frequently sought the waters for their supposed healing powers. The spring's fame spread, resulting in the village becoming known as Kampong Ayer Panas, which means "Village of Hot Water" in Malay.

Soft drinks firm Fraser & Neave (F&N) acquired the site in 1922, & set up a bottling plant at nearby Semangat Ayer to tap the mineral water, which they labelled Seletaris. During the Second World War, the spring's flow was temporarily interrupted when a bomb fell near the well during a Japanese air raid over Singapore in 1942. After the fall of Singapore, the Japanese military seized the place & converted it into recreational thermal baths (onsen).

The hot spring was frequented by gamblers in 1960, who took "good luck" baths before the start of horse races. That same year, the villagers urged the authorities to develop the area into a spa-like onsen tourist resort. However, F&N shelved the suggestion after geologists could not trace the source of the spring water. In 1967, the proposal of the spa surfaced again, when F&N proposed plans for the development of a bathhouse, restaurants, a miniature golf course & even a nature reserve. However, the plans did not materialize, so the hot spring remained untouched & forgotten.

post_caption:
Hey there! Origin Journeys is a new platform for authentic experiences in Singapore, allowing you to connect with grassroots businesses and to really be able to appreciate what our country is about. More so than that, we hope to be a force for good by channelling leisure dollars where they matter the most. Origin Journeys was conceived during this difficult period of Covid, where we went back to the drawing board and asked ourselves what travel and leisure really meant. The idea of looking at our immediate surroundings with fresh perspectives, since we're gonna be stuck here for awhile 💁🏻‍♀️, re-discovering our roots, tapping into narratives of our individual and collective heritages and being able to offer unique, personalised and homegrown experiences guided by the most knowledgeable and affable locals was foremost in our minds.

From short weekend escapades to deeper journeys into rediscovering the little nooks of our city, we offer experiences for all ages and personalities, thoughtfully crafted through our years of scouring this island for the absolute best it has to offer. 

Keep a lookout at this space for our upcoming launch campaign where you get a chance to win exciting experiences, meals at the hottest spots and a night or two at the most luxurious hotels in town!

【Sengkang #2 - Egg Tart & Siew Pau】
Occupying 24,000 square metres, the “Arts in the Park” is a sculpture garden specially-designed for the residents of Sengkang. Look out for the “Waves” sculptures which reminds us of Sengkang past as a fishing village and harbour. Many colourful textured ball sculptures are also designed to allow park users to simply sit back and laze on them. Put Sengkang Sculpture Park on the top of your to-do list when you visit Sengkang.

Our featured dimsum pastries are a satisfying snack for any time of the day. Traditionally a Cantonese cuisine, it was said that the origin of the egg tart was inspired by the English custard tart and Portuguese egg tarts. And instead of featuring the usual steamed Char Siew Pau, we’ve selected the ‘baked’ version where juicy BBQ pork is wrapped in crispy and buttery pastry. 

Make a trip to the nearest coffee shop, and keep a lookout for these savoury yummies in the window display. Best paired with a steaming glass of fragrant Kopi-O-Gao! Shiok!

Do you know of any hawkers who sell such freshly-made pastries? Comment below to tell us where you get your delicious pastries. Stay tuned for our post when we reveal the stall name and learn about our behind-the-scenes process. See ya!
